<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Blood-And-Tear Indictment Against Cult Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Feng Jian
</P>
<P>
KANUNGU, UGANDA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Lydia Bagambe, a
48-year-old widow in Kanungu, Uganda, is so ordinary-looking and
ordinarily dressed that she would not draw any attention, but she
is at the same time so extraordinary now because she is the
sister-in-law of the doomsday cult leader Credonia Mwerinde and
lost four children in the tragic church fire on March 17.
</P>
<P>
"She is a cruel devil, not at all an angel who can speak
directly with God. She kills so many people. I would tear her to
pieces if she appears before me," Lydia said about Mwerinde in an
interview with Xinhua in Kanungu county Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
With tears in her eyes, Lydia said that she lost three
daughters, aged 26, 24,23 respectively, and her only son in the
fire which she said could be nothing but a scheme.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure it's designed to kill the members of the cult
Movement for the Restoration of Ten Commandments of God. She
forced my children into cult membership and did not allow them to
come back to me," she spoke in the local dialect.
</P>
<P>
"My children joined the cult very early. They eat very bad food
there. So they escaped to home. But their aunt forced them to go
back again. My son was in primary seven when he was taken to
their church and joined the cult. He dared not talk to me about
his sufferings in the camp for fear of his aunt who became the
head of the family after my husband's death in 1980s," Lydia's
voice trembled a bit when she spoke.
</P>
<P>
After rubbing her tears with an old handkerchief, she pointed
to a three- year-old baby on her lap and added:"This is the
three-year-old girl my 26- year-old daughter left behind. She was
six months pregnant when she died. I just don't know where is my
future," the middle-aged widow cast her eyes down onto the girl
who had been looking at me with so innocent eyes all the time I
chatted with her grandma.
</P>
<P>
When asked about whether Mwerinde tried to persuade her to join
the cult,
</P>
<P>
Lydia said that Mwerinde had tried several times to get her into
the cult but failed because she was a Protestant and would not
believe in the end of the world at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
"However, my kids were young and were easily taken in. Like
many other kids playing there, my son was lovely and active and
did not know much about the world, but he was burnt to death," she
pointed to some boys playing football not far away. "This is my
kid," she added after showing me a yellowish photo of his son,"he
was denied schooling after joining the cult."
</P>
<P>
"My son once told me that there were many kids of his age in
the church. They were only allowed to take one cup of porridge
each day. Every time my son came back stealthily, I noticed he
became thinner and every time I shed silent tears for that. You
know what a mother would feel in this case, " she told me and the
large crowd around me.
</P>
<P>
When at last I asked what she thought of her sister-in-law,
Lydia said without any hesitation,"she is just a devil. She
killed so many people, innocent people. I would tear her to
pieces if she appears before me." She evidently raised her voice
when uttering the last sentence. "She would go to hell," she
cursed between her teeth.
</P>
<P>
When our talk ended, I once again noticed her tearful eyes and
the toddling girl standing beside her, waving her small tender
hand to me in
the afternoon chilly breeze. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
