<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC FMs Due to Meet on Regional Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states are to meet in the western Saudi
city of Jeddah on April 8-9 to discuss a number of important
regional issues, a senior GCC official said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi issue and the consequences resulting from Baghdad's
refusal of the United Nations Resolution 1284 will be discussed,
GCC Secretary General Jamil Al-Hujailan said in a statement in the
Saudi capital of Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting will also follow up measures and steps taken
at the GCC summit in Riyadh last November to carry out an agreement
on setting up a customs union, which will come into effect on March
1, 2005.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was believed to be a critical decision in moving
toward the economic integration of the Gulf Arab states.
</P>
<P>
The summit also approved a unified legal system for customs and
changes to real estate ownership regulations.
</P>
<P>
Al-Hujailan said GCC foreign ministers will also review the
results of efforts made by a GCC committee formed to map out a
mechanism for direct talks between the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
and Iran in order to solve the dispute over three Gulf islands.
</P>
<P>
Both the UAE and Iran declared sovereignty over the three isles
of Abu Mussa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs, in the mouth of the
strategic Strait of Hormuz. The islands are now controlled by
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The latest developments of the Middle East peace process will
also be discussed by the GCC top diplomats, Al-Hujailan was quoted
by Kuwait News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance established
in 1981, comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the UAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Unilateral Pullout Might Lead to Crisis: Shareh Warns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk
Shareh said here on Monday there is no specific time set for the
resumption of the Syrian-Israeli peace talks, warning Israeli
unilateral withdrawal from south Lebanon could trigger a crisis for
Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
"Israel's crisis in south Lebanon should turn into a crisis for
Lebanon and Syria after Israeli withdrawal," Shareh told reporters
after his meeting with visiting Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
"The question is very simple but Israel wants to complicate it.
Syria and Lebanon seek a fair and comprehensive solution and ask
for sincere implementation of the relevant U.N. Security Council
resolutions," he said, adding "Israel rejects this."
</P>
<P>
"Lebanon and Syria are ready to conclude peace deals with Israel
provided the latter withdraw fully from south Lebanon and the Golan
Heights to the international borders of June 4, 1967," according to
Shareh.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Hoss said his talks with Shareh dealt with the
peace process against the backdrop of the Geneva summit between
Syrian President Hafez al-Assad and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"Our views were identical on all the issues raised during the
meeting," the Lebanese leader said.
</P>
<P>
Describing his talks with Syrian Prime Minister Mustafa Miro
as "very fruitful," Hoss said they discussed the peace process and
the Israel-planted hurdles before it, and the bilateral ties and
ways of developing them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, assistant secretary general of the Lebanese Hezbollah
Sheikh Na'im Katem said his movement will continue its struggle and
will never offer Israel any guarantees until Israel withdraw from
Lebanon completely.
</P>
<P>
Hoss arrived here Monday morning on a one-day visit to Syria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
