<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Plane in Baghdad to Protest U.N. Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A European airplane carrying three
persons from France and Italy, landed at the Al-Rashed military
airport in Baghdad at 19:45 local time (1645 GMT), to protest the
decade-long U.N. embargo on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, the first group came to Baghdad without getting
U.N. permission after the U.N. imposed embargo on Iraq since the
latter's invasion of Kuwait in 1990, was greeted by Abdul-Razak Al-
Hashimi, chairman of the Iraqi Friendship and Peace Organization.
</P>
<P>
It is widely expected that Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq
Aziz and Foreign Minister Mohammad Said Al-Sahaf will meet the
three Europeans, one from France and two from Italy.
</P>
<P>
At the airport, Jean-Marie Benjamin, head of the delegation,
read a declaration to the local and foreign media who have been
waiting for more than seven hours.
</P>
<P>
The declaration condemned the embargo that has claimed more than
1.5 million lives, and has destroyed the social, economic and
health-care structures of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The declaration termed the U.S and British non-stop unilateral
bombardments against Iraq as "a violation of international law," "
acts of terrorism" and "a genocide."
</P>
<P>
The declaration requested the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
the member states of the U.N. Security Council to intervene as soon
as possible for "the immediate and total lifting of the embargo"
and to provide emergent and effective aid for Iraq's
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question from Xinhua, Benjamin said that the
delegation will stay in Iraq for two or three days, but they have
no immediate schedule of their activities here.
</P>
<P>
Al-Hashimi said that Iraq appreciates the courage of the
delegation.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which flew directly from Amman, capital of Jordan, is
the second European airplane arriving in Iraq since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, British Member of Parliament George Galloway
arrived here by plane to protest the U.N. sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
