<HEADLINE> Arafat: No Israeli Suggestion on Palestinian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on
Monday denied that Israel offered a suggestion on the future
Palestinian state during the recent round of Washington talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat told reporters in the West Bank city of Bethlehem after
his meeting with European Union Commissioner of Foreign Affairs
Christopher Patin.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday Palestinian chief negotiator in the interim
talks with Israel Saeb Erekat ruled out the existence of Israeli
offer to establish a Palestinian state on 50 percent of the
occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator in the final status talks Yasser
Abed Rabbo was quoted on Sunday as saying that Israel suggested to
group all the Jewish settlement blocks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The essence of Israel's suggestion is to establish a Palestinian
state on some 50 percent of the West Bank consisting of two major
parts inside Israel's boundaries without any borders with other
Arab states, Rabbo said.
</P>
<P>
However, Erekat said the Israelis did not raise such an idea.
</P>
<P>
The Washington talks focusing on the issues of land, Palestinian
refugees and the future relations between Israel and Palestine have
yet made any progress.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to hold another round of talks on April 6
in a bid to reach a framework deal by May for a permanent peace
treaty by next September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
