<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Production May Increase Again: Venezuelan Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan Oil Minister Ali
Rodriguez, the new president of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC), said Monday oil output may increase
among OPEC members this year.
</P>
<P>
He said last week's agreement in Vienna for an output hike of
about 1.7 million barrels a day would likely be insufficient. The
purpose of that hike was to bring down international oil prices
that had reached 10-year highs.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez reiterated the producer group's new price-band system
for guiding prices by regulating supplies, based on a range of 22
dollars to 28 dollars a barrel for the OPEC basket of crudes.
</P>
<P>
``If prices are below dollars 22, we'll cut production by 500,
000 barrels a day and when prices are above dollars 28 a barrel,
we'll increase production,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, nine OPEC members agreed to boost output quotas by 1.
452 million barrels a day starting April 1, restoring the cuts
made a year ago in an effort to boost prices and stabilize the
market.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, the largest oil exporter in the Western Hemisphere,
promised to cut 12,5000 bpd within the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
