<HEADLINE> Annan Prefers Israel's Pullout from Southern Lebanon Part of Broader Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said on Monday that he preferred Israel's withdrawal
from southern Lebanon was part of a broader agreement between
Israel, Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Asked about Israel's intention to pull out with or without
prior agreement with Lebanon and Syria, Annan said in a press
conference at the headquarters in New York that he believed that
there was "some movement " on the Lebanon question.
</P>
<P>
"If the withdrawal comes outside a broader agreement,
obviously it's not an ideal situation", he said, adding the United
Nations would have to cope with that possibility.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he would meet Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
in Geneva On Tuesday to discuss Israel's withdrawal from southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Noting that a U.N. force is stationed in southern Lebanon under
1978 Security Council resolution, Annan said "I think we will have
to discuss with the parties and see how we carry on our
responsibilities."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon was established to
restore the Lebanese Government's authority over the southern part
of the country after a 1978 Israeli incursion against Palestinian
guerrillas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
