<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Outlines Environmental Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- George W. Bush, Texas governor
of the United States, Monday unveiled a six-point plan for
cleaning and redeveloping polluted industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the site of a former steel plant that was
cleaned up in southern Pittsburgh, the presumed Republican
presidential nominee said states have successfully begun cleaning
and reusing brownfields, so the federal government should
accelerate work on some 450,000 remaining sites.
</P>
<P>
Bush, in an attempt to answer Vice President Al Gore's
environmental credentials while showing he is a government
reformer, urged Americans to put priority on preserving the
environment.
</P>
<P>
"Prosperity will mean little if we leave to future generations
a world of polluted air, toxic lakes and rivers and banished
forests," said Bush.
</P>
<P>
The governor's proposal could help blunt criticism of
environmental problems in Texas, where air pollution in Houston
recently surpassed that of Los Angeles, observers said.
</P>
<P>
His proposals include directing the Environmental Protection
Agency to set high standards for brownfield cleanups, giving
developers who clean up brownfields under state redevelopment
plans protection from future federal legal action, focusing the
federal government on developing technologies and methods to clean
brownfields.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposals, Bush would also streamline bureaucracy and
block grants money under the 35 million dollar Brownfield Cleanup
Revolving Loan Fund, extend permanently a brownfield cleanup tax
credit that is scheduled to expire on December 31 and direct
active federal facilities to comply with all environmental
protection laws and hold them accountable when they do not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0021 </DOCNO>
