<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DRC Accuses Uganda, Rwanda of Failure to Respect U.N. Resolution, Calls for U.N. Deployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) Monday accused both Uganda and Rwanda, supporters of
the rebel movement to topple the DRC Government, of the failure to
honor their commitment to cease-fire and the U.N. Security Council
resolution 1291, calling for an early deployment of U.N. military
observers and peace-keepers in the Central African country.
</P>
<P>
Andre Mwamba Kapanga, DRC's permanent representative to the
United Nations, told a press conference here that his government
would "cooperate fully" with the United Nations in carrying out
the resolution.
</P>
<P>
"Regrettably, there has not been any improvement in the
process since the adoption of the new calendar and the Security
Council resolution 1291" in January when a mini-summit, which
attracted heads of state of the countries involved in the conflict
in DRC, was held at the U.N. Headquarters in New York, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the northwestern part of our country, Uganda has been
consistently in attack our forces," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Both Uganda and Rwanda had no intention of respecting the new
calendar ... or the resolution 1291," he said. "And they are
intent on continuing to plunder the resources of the Democratic
Republic of the Congo."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the DRC ambassador also criticized some members of
the Security Council for insisting on cease-fire first before the
start of the U.N. military deployment in the country, formerly
known as Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time through the U.N. that I heard members
of the U.N., the Security Council and the Secretariat said that
before we can go, bring peace in that area. We have to have a
cease-fire," he said.
</P>
<P>
"When the U.N. was involved in East Timor, for example,
shooting was taking place when the U.N. sent its solders there,"
he said. "The war was going on even in Kosovo, the U.N. was
involved to certain extent at a time when shooting was taking
place."
</P>
<P>
"In Bosnia, in Croatia, you had fighting going on and the U.N.
went there," he said. "In the case of the Congo, they said that
you have to have cease-fire ahead of time before the U.N. could go.
"
</P>
<P>
"There was a long period" during which "nobody was shooting" in
the central and southern parts of the DRC, "the U.N. never sent
soldiers there," he said. "My feeling is that people have to be
sincere, you either go to the Congo to bring peace, and help the
people and stop the misery, the suffering, the death ...in the
country, or you just let them die."
</P>
<P>
"I think that so far, the Security Council has chosen the
latter, that is not to intervene despite the fact many people are
dying," he said.
</P>
<P>
The many-sided DRC war has forced 1.3 million people from their
homes and created a humanitarian disaster, Ross Mountain, director
of the U.N.'s Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs
in Geneva, said that 1.4 million Congolese out of a total
population of around 48 million were short of food and health care
as a result of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The DRC ambassador said that his government has not known that
the U.N. has deployed any soldiers in his country despite a
technical team was in the country to make preparations.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations said that the current fighting in the
African country has stunted the deployment of 500 military
observers and 5,000 peace-keepers to monitor the shaky peace
process beginning with the signing of a peace accord in Lusaka,
Zambia, in July and August by the DRC Government and its allies
and the rebels trying to oust President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The DRC conflict broke out in August 1998 shortly before Angola,
Namibia and Zimbabwe sent soldiers to fight with Kabila against
rebels, backed by Uganda and Rwanda.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
