<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Gets $3 Billion From 10-year Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government has
 benefited a total of three billion U.S. dollars from the
privatization process since it started in 1990, it was disclosed
at a seminar held here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Director General of the Tanzania Investment Center (TIC) Samwel
Sitta told the cross-border investment and political risk
management seminar that about 110,000 jobs have been created in
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania stands a good chance to perform even better in the
private sector if it improves efficiency and encourage foreign and
local investors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sitta, however, complained that the cost of doing business in
Tanzania is too high and that there are conflicting policies, laws
and regulations on investment as well as the administrative
cumbersome procedures.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to equip the TIC with more powers so as
to enable it to become an effective facilitator for small, medium
and big investment in the country to improve lives of millions of
Tanzanians currently living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
Another senior Tanzanian official told the seminar that the
major macro economic and fiscal reforms carried out since 1995
have brought about a drastic reduction in inflation to seven
percent from as high as 35 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State in the President's Office Nassoro Malocho
said there has been an increased Gross Domestic Product (GDP) at
between five and six percent in the year 1998/99 and that the
interest rates have been stabilized at between 10 and 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Malocho said that Tanzania is primarily an agricultural economy
that generates about 50 percent of the total GDP and approximately
80 percent of the entire population depend directly on agriculture
and related sectors for their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
"The government has welcomed investors to participate in
large-scale farming," he said. "However, there has been a slow
response because the investment cost on agriculture infrastructure
is expensive and the investors want more assurance on land laws
before their investment."
</P>
<P>
The two-day seminar drew participants from the World Bank,
Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the seminar, Governor of the Uganda Central Bank
Charles Kikonyogo said the East African countries should make
plans while learning from the past mistakes so as to build
stronger economies and that removal of tariffs will encourage
cross border investment.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania like many other countries in Sub-Saharan Africa has
in the past decade put in place reform measures that are turning
the country into a business friendly investment destination," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
