<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Fresh Start of Ties with Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- At the opening of the first Africa-
Europe summit here Monday, the European Union (EU) called for a
fresh start of the relations with Africa which it described as
the "main victim" of unfair global relationships.
</P>
<P>
"It is our profound wish that this most meaningful occasion
should represent a moment of renewal in the relations between our
two neighboring continents," European Union Council President
Antonio Guterres said in a speech at the summit attended by over 60
leaders of African and EU states.
</P>
<P>
Guterres, who is prime minister of Portugal, which holds the
rotating EU presidency, told the leaders that the summit's "
profoundly symbolic nature" should be "rich in consequences" for
Africans and Europeans.
</P>
<P>
"The African continent has been the main victim of the unfair
character of the present architecture of international relations.
This is both unacceptable and unsustainable," he said in the
conference center in the Egyptian capital.
</P>
<P>
"Africa must not be marginalized in the economic and
technological revolution that we are all undergoing," Guterres
said.
</P>
<P>
"That is why we share the concern of African leaders for the
burden of external debt, for open market access to their products,
for investment and technological flows, for international aid to
development," he added.
</P>
<P>
The summit is to discuss economic, political together with
social problems in Africa and seek ways of boosting cooperation
between Africa and the EU in resolving the issues.
</P>
<P>
To show the continuation of the efforts, African and EU foreign
ministers agreed on Sunday that a ministerial group will be set up
to follow up what will be decided by the leaders and that a second
summit will be held in 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
