<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Commission President Envisages Better EU- Libya Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Romano Prodi, president of the
Commission of the European Union (EU), expressed confidence here on
Monday that the relations between the EU and Libya "will be
better."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the opening ceremony of the first
Africa-Europe summit, Prodi said that his meeting with Libyan
leader Muammar Gaddafi earlier in the day would help develop good
relations between Europe and the North African country.
</P>
<P>
Prodi and Gaddafi were in Cairo to take part in the two-day
summit also attended by leaders of other African and EU countries
to discuss economic, political and social issues in Africa and seek
EU's efforts to help promote African development.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said that in the meeting, Gaddafi also showed willingness
for improving relations with Europe.
</P>
<P>
Ties between European countries and Libya had been marred by the
Europeans' accusation that tripoli was supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
However, their relations began easing up after Libya handed over
last year the two Libyans suspected of bombing a Pan-Am flight in
1988 over Lockerbie, Scotland, which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council imposed diplomatic, air and
arms sanctions on Libya in 1992 for its refusal to surrender the
suspects. The sanctions have been suspended after the handover.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Gaddafi's attitude towards the cooperation between
North African countries and the EU within the framework of the so-
called Barcelona process, Prodi said that the Libyan leader was not
directly interested in the process, "but he is not against it."
</P>
<P>
The 15 EU member states and 12 Mediterranean rim countries
signed in 1995 in Spain the Barcelona Declaration, which was aimed
at creating an area for free trade and with common political and
security policies by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on his meeting with Gaddafi, Prodi said it is
important that "we have opened a dialog." "It is not the last page
in our book," he added, hinting at more meetings between Europe and
Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
