<HEADLINE> First Africa-Europe Summit Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- African leaders at the opening
session of the first Africa-Europe summit Monday called on Africa
and the European Union (EU) to forge better cooperation for mutual
benefits and universal progress.
</P>
<P>
"We do look forward not to securing more aid, but rather to
developing our mutual partnership and cooperation program," said
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, who inaugurated the two-day
summit in the International Conference Center in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Africa seeks to support its sustained efforts on all levels to
achieve a comprehensive revival for the continent, in a way that
allows Africa to occupy the position it deserves, Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Africans hope to establish "a new form of close partnership"
with EU countries, "based on common interests and mutual benefits,
to realize prosperity and welfare" for both sides, he added.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the 15 EU members states are former colonial powers in
Africa and the EU gives 15 billion U.S. dollars to Africa every
five years, more than any other single source.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing summit is co-sponsored by the EU and the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) with an aim to forge new and
strategic partnership between the two continents in the 21st
century and in the economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
Heads of state or government, or their representatives from 66
African and European states are attending the summit.
</P>
<P>
Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika, whose country is
holding the presidency of the OAU also said at the opening session
that "let this historic site be a witness to a new departure, a
veritable renewal of these links, for the furtherance of mutual
understanding and universal progress."
</P>
<P>
He noted that Africa has been aware of backwardness and risk of
being pushed even further outside of the general movement of
progress with the advent of economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. figures, half of the continent's 700 million
population are living in poverty. For years, most African countries
have remained as major suppliers of raw materials to the world
market due to the lack of industrial basis.
</P>
<P>
The heave external debts that have reached staggering 350
billion dollars, widespread wars and conflicts and diseases have
further worsened the economic situation on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The poor investment environment has in turn scared away foreign
investors. Scarcely 1 percent of direct foreign investment has been
channelled to Africa during the last two years.
</P>
<P>
Bouteflika said Africa is concerned about "being locked for good
in the tragic reality."
</P>
<P>
Bouteflika highlighted the debt issue in his speech, urging EU,
the major creditor of Africa, to handle the debt issue not
according to the African states' capability of reimbursement, but
with an eye on mutual benefit and joint development in the long
run.
</P>
<P>
African states are spending 23 billion dollars, or 30.9 percent
of their exports, every year to service the enormous sum of
external debts. Little money was left for the African countries for
further public investment, technical upgrade and economic
expansion.
</P>
<P>
Most African countries have cried for EU steps for easing the
debt burden and regarded the summit as an opportunity to address
the issue.
</P>
<P>
On ways of solving African problems and promoting the
continent's development, Bouteflika urged the EU to take into
consideration the actual conditions of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The EU has initially seen the summit as a political event,
highlighting democracy, conflict prevention, human rights,
different from Africa's pressing economic concerns.
</P>
<P>
The two sides smoothed out their differences at the eleventh
hour ahead of the summit to discuss economic as well as political
issues.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guterres, whose country
initiated the summit and is holding the EU presidency, also
addressed the opening session.
</P>
<P>
He said "it is our profound wish that this most meaningful
occasion should represent a moment of renewal in the relationship
between our two neighboring continents."
</P>
<P>
He stressed the new development in the world, such as the rapid
development of technology, the advent of information society and
economic globalization, "must not create a divide between us and
our neighbors... they must create new opportunities to share
political, economic and cultural development based on fundamental
shared values."
</P>
<P>
He also noted the equal footing on African economic, social and
political issues, saying EU will cooperate with African states in
solving their problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
