<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece to Deregulate Energy, Telecoms by 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Greece will deregulate its energy
and telecommunications markets by 2001 in a bid to speed up the
pace of the country's privatization.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with the state televison NET network
Monday, Greek Economy and Finance Minister Yiannos Papantoniou
said that the state-run Public Power Corporation (PPC) would be
floated in the stock market in November this year and the
corporation would from 2001 lose its monopoly in electricity
supply.
</P>
<P>
With the aim of benefiting Greeks through lower electricity
rates and seeking better services arising from stronger
competition in the energy market, other companies would also be
allowed to produce electricity power from then on, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the Greek government would also seek a
strategic partner for the state-operated the Hellenic
Telecommunications Organization (OTE) this Autumn, and from next
year, other private companies would be able to offer alternative
telephone services in the country.
</P>
<P>
Papantoniou said that this would offer OTE access to
international markets and to new technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
