<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Calls for Closer Afro-EU Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- At the historic Africa-Europe summit
which opened Monday, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak called on
Africa and the European Union (EU) to forge better cooperation for
mutual benefits.
</P>
<P>
"We do look forward not to securing more aid, but rather to
developing our mutual partnership and cooperation program," Mubarak
said in an inaugural speech.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of 53 African countries and the 15 EU nations are
participating in the summit, which is to discuss economic,
political and social issues in Africa and explore ways to enhance
African-EU cooperation in these aspects.
</P>
<P>
Africa seeks to support its sustained efforts on all levels to
achieve a comprehensive revival for the continent, in a way that
allows Africa to occupy the position it deserves, Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Africans hope to establish "a new form of close partnership"
with EU countries, "based on common interests and mutual benefits,
to realize prosperity and welfare" for both sides, he added.
</P>
<P>
"It is worth mentioning that African countries have made
significant strides over the past decade to create a favorable
atmosphere to pave the way for overcoming the problems it has
suffered for years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Those strides included "economic restructuring reform" and
establishing "pillars of democracy, freedom, and respect for human
rights and the rule of law," the Egyptian leader added.
</P>
<P>
Drawing attention to the Africans' dominant concern at the
summit, Mubarak said "unfavorable external conditions" were to
blame for their continent's staggering 350 billion U.S. dollars in
foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Those conditions included a "tangible drop" in foreign funds
going into Africa over the past two decades, declining prices for
raw materials, and Africa's small share of world trade, he said.
</P>
<P>
Africa's export accounted for 6 percent of the world's total
years ago, but the share has declined to 2 percent now.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the Cairo summit will "give a strong
impetus" to efforts by Algeria and South Africa on behalf of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) to convince lending countries "
to ease debt burdens and service costs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
