<HEADLINE> Erekat Denies Israeli Suggestion on Area of Palestinian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian chief negotiator in the
interim talks Saeb Erekat has denied a reported Israeli suggestion
on establishing the Palestinian state on 50 percent of the West
Bank, said the Palestinian News Agency on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Erekat's remarks referred to the reports that cited Palestinian
chief negotiator in the final-status talks Yasser Abed Rabbo as
saying on Sunday that Israel proposed to the Palestinians last week
to hand over two settlements in the West Bank as part of the future
Palestinian Independent state in lieu of annexing the rest of the
West Bank to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Rabbo who headed the Palestinian side in the peace talks with
Israel in Washington last week has reportedly said the essence of
the Israeli suggestion is to establish a Palestinian state on 50
percent of the West Bank, which has no borders with any Arab
countries and to be surrounded by Israeli from all directions.
</P>
<P>
However, Erekat said the Israeli side did not suggest such a
state.
</P>
<P>
The Washington talks focusing on the land issue, the Palestinian
refugees and the future relations between Israel and Palestine have
not achieved any progress.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side insists on the implementation of the
relevant U.N. Security Council resolution on top of which are the
Resolution No. 242 and the Resolution No. 338, Erekat noted.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians also stick to the reference of the Madrid Peace
Conference enshrining land-for-peace principle and to the Israeli
withdrawal from all territories occupied in 1967 including
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to hold a new round of talks on April 6 to
reach a framework agreement by May as a prelude to signing a
permanent peace accord by September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
