<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libyan Leader Meets EU Commission President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi
insisted on the priority Libya attaches to close relations with
Europe both on a bilateral scale and in the framework of a regional
cooperation with other Northern African Mediterranean countries.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi voiced the stance in meeting with European Union
Commission President Romano Prodi Monday just ahead of the Africa-
Europe summit that opened Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Gaddafi-Prodi talks, taking place by Gaddafi's spacious tent
erected in the presidential palace, is the Libyan leader's first
such meeting since U.N. sanctions on Libya were suspended last year
after the Northern Africa state surrended the two suspects in a
1988 bombing of an American flight.
</P>
<P>
Libya's statements on Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) have dented its chances of joining the "Barcelona
process," which kicked off in 1995 the political, economic, social
and security cooperation between the 15-member EU and 12
Mediterranean rim countries. 
</P>
<P>
Libya has said it accepts the EU's conditions for joining the
process. But it said the participation of Israel and the PNA would
have a negative influence, and they should be excluded until there
was a "just peace" in the region. 
</P>
<P>
EU officials have said this position is unacceptable. 
</P>
<P>
The European Union has asked for a clear acceptance, without
conditions and in written form, of the Barcelona "acquis" from
Libya. The acquis, or rules, include commitments to human
rights, democracy, regional stability and free trade.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi also made clear that he accepts that the Barcelona
acquis as reiterated by President Prodi is not negotiable by the
EU.
</P>
<P>
He also acknowledged the contributions made by the EU
Commission, the executive arm of the EU, to the development of
Africa and the active role of the EU in facing dramatic problems
like debts, poverty and struggle against endemic diseases.
</P>
<P>
The leaders came to Cairo for the first two-day Africa-Europe
summit, which involved heads of state or government, or their
representatives from most of the 53 African states and all the 15
EU members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
