<HEADLINE> Half Britons See Euro Membership by 2010: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Fifty percent of Britons believe
Britain will have joined the European single currency by 2010
whether they like it or not, according to an opinion poll
published on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Gallop poll for the Daily Telegraph newspaper showed that
46 percent believed Britain would not join the euro by then.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-four percent believed euro membership would be a bad
development for Britain and only 32 percent thought it would be
good.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed 49 percent of Britons believed control over
foreign policy would be removed from London to the European Union'
s headquarters in Brussels during the coming decade, while 42
percent said it wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
A majority believed Britain's environmental policy and
employment legislation would also be run from Brussels by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Forty-one percent said Britain's standard of living would fall
if the country left the European Union, while 16 percent said it
would rise. Thirty-nine percent said it would remain the same.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair favors joining the euro after the
next general election, provided economic conditions are right and
a referendum approves the move. The next general election must be
held by May 2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
