<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Says His Millennium Report Resolutely Forward-looking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said on Monday that his Millennium Report was
resolutely forward-looking and a comprehensive account of the main
challenges facing humanity in the twenty-first century.
</P>
<P>
The Millennium Report titled "We the Peoples: The role of the
United Nations in the 21st century" was launched here today in
which the Secretary-General sets out a practical vision for the
United Nations in a globalized world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Annan said the report contains some
pretty alarming facts, particularly on the environment, and also
some pretty shaming ones, particularly on poverty.
</P>
<P>
It shows that the world has been far too tolerant of gross
injustice and human misery, and it argues that must be changed,
the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
"The world's political leaders have agreed to meet here in New
York in September, in the largest gathering at such a high level
there has ever been," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"Their peoples would be gravely disappointed if they simply
came here, made a few speeches, and went away again. They need to
agree on the most urgent tasks we face together, and to adopt a
strategy for carrying them out," he said.
</P>
<P>
"While governments do have to work together to make these
changes possible, governments alone are not going to make them
happen. Much of the heavy lifting will be done by private
investment, partnerships with philanthropic foundations will also
be very important," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The overall message is that these are problems we share, and
that we have a common interest in solving them. And they are
problems we can deal with, if only we summon the will," Annan
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
