<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Adopts Tough Measures on Asylum Seekers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Tough new measures came into force
in Britain on Monday aimed at deterring asylum seekers, replacing
cash payments to refugees with vouchers and fining lorry drivers
for carrying stowaways.
</P>
<P>
The Labor government says the Immigration and Asylum Act should
speed up a labyrinthine process and make life fairer for those
truly in need. But refugee rights groups reacted angrily to the
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
"What we are offering is putting in place a system which
supports and helps those genuinely seeking asylum but which is
there also to deter people who make completely unfounded claims
and bring the whole system of asylum into disrepute," the Reuters
quoted Immigration Minister Barbara Roche as saying.
</P>
<P>
The measures came into force as Britain is gripped by a
controversy over the treatment of refugees. Rising numbers of
European beggars on London's streets and in the Tube, the capital'
s underground railway, have led to a campaign by some popular
newspapers saying the country is swamped by illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
At present, about 80 percent of asylum seekers are concentrated
in London and the southeast. The government says the financial
burden must now be shared out more widely.
</P>
<P>
It plans to disperse asylum seekers across the country, despite
fears that this will cut off refugees from their key support
networks.
</P>
<P>
The government says it wants to help genuine refugees and is
getting to grips with the backlog of asylum cases, currently
standing at more than 100,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
