<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Member States' Commitment to Ending Poverty, Inequality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Monday called on the Member States to commit themselves
to ending poverty and inequality.
</P>
<P>
In his Millennium Report" We the Peoples, The role of the
United Nations in the 21st century" launched here today, Annan
said the benefits of globalization include faster economic growth,
higher living standards and diffusion of technology and management
skills for individuals and countries alike.
</P>
<P>
"But these benefits remain highly concentrated among a
relatively small number of countries and are spread unevenly
within them," the U.N, chief noted.
</P>
<P>
"While there are now strong and well enforced rules
facilitating the expansion of global markets, efforts to secure
equally valid social objectives such as labor standards, the
environment, human rights or poverty reduction, have lagged behind,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
"The challenge is clear, if we are to capture the promises of
globalization while managing its adverse effects, we must learn to
govern better, and we must learn how better to govern together,"
he sad.
</P>
<P>
Annan urged the world to halve by 2015 the proportion of the
world's people whose income is less than one dollars a day.
</P>
<P>
"The world's people are telling us that our past achievements
are not enough, given the scale of the challenges we face, we must
do more, and we must do it better," Annan added.
</P>
<P>
The report is prepared for the Millennium Summit of the United
Nations to be held from September 6 to 8 in New York which is
expected to be the largest-ever gathering of heads of State and
Government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
