<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Visas For Life" Exhibit Opens at U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A series of events are
scheduled to take place from morning to night on Monday at the U.N.
Headquarters in New York, with the opening of the exhibit "Visas
For Life: The Righteous Diplomats."
</P>
<P>
The exhibit was designated to honor more than 80 diplomats,
including who risked their lives and livelihood to rescue Jews and
other refugees during the Holocaust (1938-1945), Eric Saul, one of
the exhibit organizers, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Fengshan Ho, the Chinese Consul General in Vienna during
World War II, is among the diplomats honored at the exhibition for
his decision to issue life-saving visas to the Jews in the German-
occupied Austria.
</P>
<P>
Ho was one of the first diplomats to save Jews by issuing them
visas to Shanghai, East China, to escape the Nazis, who exercised
fiercely hostile policy toward Jews during the World War II.
</P>
<P>
The exhibit and programs are cosponsored by the Office of the
United Nations High Commission and other institutions such as the
American Jewish Committee, the World Jewish Congress and the
Jewish National Fund.
</P>
<P>
Manli Ho, daughter of Dr. Ho, told Xinhua that his father "
remain completely unknown, even by the people he had saved," for
many years.
</P>
<P>
Harry Fiedler, son of the parents who got the Chinese life-
saving visa before his birth in Shanghai, told Xinhua, "Without Dr.
Ho, I wouldn't be here today."
</P>
<P>
Born in September 1901 in Yiyang, Hunan Province in Central
China, Ho died in September 1997 in San Francisco at 96.
</P>
<P>
Of the four still living, two -- Jan Karski, former Consul
General of Poland, and Selahattin Ulkumen, former Turkish Consul
General to Rhodes -- attended the opening of the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
There will be a special viewing of the exhibit for invited
guests and families of both the diplomats and those they rescued,
followed by a convocation in the General Assembly Hall on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
Nane Annan, wife of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, will
speak at the convocation, and Wang Yingfan, the Chinese permanent
representative to the United Nations, will attend the convocation,
diplomatic sources here said.
</P>
<P>
A number of diplomats honored in the exhibit lost their lives
during this heroic rescue. Collectively, they saved more than 250,
000 lives. Today, there are more than 500,000 living descendants
of these survivors and refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
