<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Report Says Countries Falling Back on Commitment to End Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Countries are not doing
enough to reduce poverty in their societies, according to a new
United Nations Development Program (UNDP) report to be released
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report, "Overcoming Human Poverty: UNDP Poverty Report
2000," states that while more than 75 percent of poor nations have
measured the extent and dimensions of poverty in their societies,
less than a third have set targets for reducing it.
</P>
<P>
The report calls on the developed and developing countries to
renew their efforts to eradicate poverty by strengthening
governance and by empowering people to improve their livelihood
and opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"Old-school prescriptions of supplementing rapid growth with
social spending and safety nets have proved inadequate," the
report's authors said.
</P>
<P>
In the foreword to the report, UNDP Administrator Mark Brown
said, "We should aim to help build up the capacities of
governments, at both national and local levels, to assume control
and direct their own initiatives. This is the vitally important
capacity-building agenda for external assistance."
</P>
<P>
Most of the developed countries have long failed to honor
their commitment to earmark 0.7 percent of their Gross National
Product for Official Development Assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
