<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Refutes Robinson's Complaints on Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A ranking Russian official on
Monday dismissed complaints by U.N. High Commissioner for Human
Rights Mary Robinson about her trip to the war-torn Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Kalamanov, the Russian presidential human rights envoy
to the breakaway republic, said Robinson was incorrect when she
asserted that she had not been allowed to visit the places in
Chechnya that she wanted to see.
</P>
<P>
Russia was unable to organize a visit to Katyr-Yurt because it
had not been put on the itinerary for her trip to the breakaway
republic,the Interfax news agency quoted Kalamanov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kalamanov described Robinson's claim as a "common lie."
</P>
<P>
He also rejected rumors that tens of thousands of people were
held in detention facilities in Chechnya, stressing that there
were only 848 names on a list of people detained by the Interior
Ministry troops.
</P>
<P>
Kalamanov said the human rights office in Chechnya has received
around 2,500 complaints about various human rights violations in
the past month.
</P>
<P>
"The passport problem must be resolved for the refugees. The
people cannot move about without (identity) documents. Chechnya
has already received 100,000 new passports, and I expect the
situation to be resolved soon," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kalamanov complained of Robinson's biased stance.
</P>
<P>
"As I said, it would be very difficult to restore the Chechens'
trust, but why is such mistrust is displayed by the high
commissioner?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
"When we talk with Mrs. Robinson one-on-one, no problems arise.
As soon as Mrs. Robinson's suite appears, she immediately changes,
"Kalamanov said, adding that he was confused by Robinson's
behavior.
</P>
<P>
Hypocrisy as regards the issue of Chechnya must be removed in
relations between Russia and the West, Kalamanov said.
</P>
<P>
"We will not allow anyone to put the bandits and terrorists on
the same level with the Russian military and government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Robinson is expected to present her report on Chechnya at a U.N.
Commission for Human Rights conference on April 5.
</P>
<P>
She met earlier Monday with Russian Emergency Situations
Minister Sergei Shoigu in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Robinson also held a meeting with Colonel General Valery
Manilov,first deputy Chief of Staff of the Russian Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
"In the course of a detailed conversation, an understanding was
achieved on the need to study thoroughly and comprehensively all
reports on human rights violation that alleged to happen in the
North Caucasus," Manilov told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
According to Manilov, Robinson agreed that "The truth must be
established in every particular case, and it is only on this basis
that reports to the public, political statements and conclusions
should be made." 
</P>
</TEXT>
