<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Government Supports Labor Movement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Jacob Zuma Monday reaffirmed his government's support
for a strong labor movement.
</P>
<P>
Zuma was speaking at the 17th World Congress of the
International Confederation of Trade Unions in Durban amid growing
tension between the government and the Congress of South African
Trade Unions (COSATU) over the federation's anti-unemployment
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The congress, which is being attended by about 1000 labor
delegates from across the world, is jointly hosted by COSATU,
National Congress of Trade Unions and Federated Unions of South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
"We are firmly in favour of a strong, well-organized, visionary
and independent trade union movement as this can only be to the
advantage of the transformation project in our country," Zuma
said.
</P>
<P>
His comments came as COSATU continued its countrywide campaign
against, among others, job losses, which will culminate in a
national strike by COSATU's 1.8 million members on May 10.
</P>
<P>
COSATU has claimed that since 1994 there have been 500,000 job
losses. It started its campaign on January 31, with various unions
affiliated to the federation organizing workplace protests and
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
Zuma told the conference that growing unemployment remained one
of the biggest challenges facing trade unions, not only in South
Africa, but also across the world.
</P>
<P>
He said there were still insufficient flows of foreign
investment into African countries, which was vital to their
economic prospects such as job creation.
</P>
<P>
He called on trade unions to focus on issues such as debt
relief and protectionist practices by developed countries who
continually failed to open up markets to developing nations on
favorable conditions.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that trade unions in developed countries invest a
percentage of their retirement and annuity funds towards job
retention and creation in developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
