<HEADLINE> SADC Biodiversity Forum Opens In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Southern African Development
Community (SADC) Biodiversity Forum opened here on Monday with
delegates calling for the intensification of efforts to seek
regional consensus on important biological issues.
</P>
<P>
The three-day forum comes ahead of a conference of parties to
the United Nation's Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) to be
held in Nairobi next month.
</P>
<P>
The participants said while SADC countries are signatories to
the convention in their individual capacities, there is need to
speak with one voice.
</P>
<P>
They felt that the accession of SADC into the CBD would enable
the region to have access to more resources for projects and
activities aimed at coordinating a regional approach to
conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
The participants agreed that discussion to find a way around
the accession issue should continue at the forum while solutions
would be forwarded to the council of ministers.
</P>
<P>
The forum also seeks to review the progress made by members
states in developing country strategies, preparing and
implementing national action plans relating to biodiversity
conservation.
</P>
<P>
Other objectives include sharing experiences on appropriate
mechanisms for effective and sustainable ways of information
exchange on biodiversity conservation among SADC member states.
</P>
</TEXT>
