<HEADLINE> Nuclear Waste Transport Stopped In Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A planned transport of highly
radioactive nuclear waste was stopped by a Judge in Belgium, local
media said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The judge in the Belgian town of Dendermonde stopped the
transport Sunday night on the territory of the town in the
Province of East Flanders.
</P>
<P>
The judge made the decision after he agreed with a claim of
Greenpeace, the environmental organization, that relevant safety
measures were inadequate.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian government had agreed to a first shipment of
nuclear waste from a reprocessing plant in France to Mol in the
Belgian Province of Antwerp.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian Ministry of Interior said it will appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
Last week, three cities in this country said they would ban the
transport of the highly toxic waste on their territories. The
three cities are Mol, Geel and Dessel. 
</P>
