<HEADLINE> Israeli Senior Official Invited to Visit Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli official has
been invited to visit Libya, a signal that the two countries may
begin to improve their bilateral relations, Israel Radio reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ra'anan Cohen, Secretary-General of Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's Labor party, received the official invitation to begin the
ice-breaking tour in the near future, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was extended by head of a Libyan delegation to
the inter-parliamentary convention on security and cooperation of
Mediterranean countries, which is currently meeting in Marseilles,
France.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Israel's Ha'aretz daily reported that the
European Union (EU) is behind the scene to press Libyan leader
Muammar Gaddafi to recognize Israel.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi is to meet some European leaders on the sidelines of the
first Africa-Europe summit, held in Cairo, Egypt on Monday and
Tuesday and attended by leaders from most of 53 African countries
and the 15-member EU in an effort to create joint partnership
between the two continents.
</P>
<P>
It is still unknown whether Ra'anan Cohen's tour of Libya has
connection with the EU's pressure or not.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the EU and the U.S. is trying hard to end
Israel's isolation among its Arab neighbors. Last week, a group of
Israeli passport holders received a warm welcome in their visit to
Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Libya is also seeking more amicable relations with
Western countries since last April, when it handed over two
suspects in the Lockerbie bombing of Pan Am flight 103 in 1988,
which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which has designated Libya as a state sponsor
of terrorism since 1979 and imposed comprehensive unilateral
sanctions causing US oil companies and investors to pull out in
1986, is reportedly considering lifting the embargo.
</P>
<P>
Washington believes Libya has also changed its opposition
attitude toward the Israeli-Palestinian peace track.  
</P>
