<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Rises in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Spending on construction
projects around the country rose 1.5 percent in February to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 758.7 billion U.S. dollars, an
all-time high monthly level, the Commerce Department said Monday.
</P>
<P>
It marked the fifth straight month in which construction
spending rose. In January, construction spending grew by 2.2
percent, slightly less than the 2.7 percent increase the
government previously estimated.
</P>
<P>
Robust construction and housing activity helped fuel the U.S.
economy's strong growth last year. Monday's report suggested that
construction activity remains at healthy levels despite the
Federal Reserve has raised the interest rates five times since
June in an effort to slow the economic growth and prevent
inflation from escalating.
</P>
<P>
The construction report said that spending on all private
construction projects grew by 2 percent in February to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 579.6 billion dollars,
reflecting higher spending on commercial and some residential
projects.
</P>
<P>
Among private projects, spending on all nonresidential, or
commercial building such as factory plants and hotels, rose 4.8
percent to 197 billion dollars. Meanwhile, spending on all
residential projects rose by 0.6 percent to a rate of 340.7
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report also showed that spending on big government projects
fell to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 179.2 billion dollars
in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
