<HEADLINE> Outlook For World Wheat Production In 2000/01 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- On the basis of information
currently available world wheat production is forecast at 590
million tons, compared with 584 million in 1999, according to the
International Grains Council (IGC).
</P>
<P>
Significant increases in area are expected in some major
growing regions, and underlie projected rises in output in the EC,
Russia, Canada and Argentina, the IGC added.
</P>
<P>
The volume of world wheat trade will largely depend on the
outcome of the new season's harvests, especially in a year when
stocks in some key importers are at low levels.
</P>
<P>
It is believed renewed economic growth and recent increases in
oil prices, if maintained, could boost demand in various countries.
</P>
<P>
At his early stage, the IGC said the world wheat trade in 2000/
01 is projected at 102 million tons, compared with the estimate of
104 million for 1999/2000.
</P>
<P>
World wheat consumption is forecast at a record 600 million
tons with food use at 442 million. Population growth remains the
strongest long-term influence, the IGC said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
