<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Launches Ambitious 21st Century Action Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-
General Kofi Annan launched here Monday a detailed report setting
the agenda for the U.N. Millennium Summit scheduled for early
September, setting an ambitious 21st century action plan for all
member nations.
</P>
<P>
In the 58-page report, entitled "We the People: The Role of
the United Nations in the 21st Century", Annan called on all
member states to commit themselves to ending poverty and
inequality, improving education, increasing security, reducing HIV/
AIDS and protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
The report, designed to set out a practical vision for the
United Nations in a globalized world, will be considered by the
Millennium Summit, the largest-ever gathering of heads of state or
government, to be held from September 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
Among its key concepts is the need to make globalization more
inclusive, to create more opportunities for all and not leave
entire continents and billions of people behind in squalor.
</P>
<P>
"The benefits of globalization remain highly concentrated
among a relatively small number of countries and are spread
unevenly within them, "said the Secretary-General.
</P>
<P>
The report observes that globalization has eluded Africa,
where many of the world's poor live, including up to 40 million
children who will be orphans by 2010, largely because of HIV/AIDS.
In addition, growth is anemic, trade and investment are low, and
national debts are crushing.
</P>
<P>
While there were strong and well enforced rules facilitating
the expansion of global markets, efforts to secure equally valid
social objectives such as labor standards, the environment, human
rights or poverty reduction, had lagged behind, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
On conflicts and peacekeeping, the U.N. chief said that
nations must address both old and new threats.
</P>
<P>
There are still too many nuclear weapons, as well as a growing
proliferation of small arms that serve to prolong and deepen
already vicious conflicts, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Peace operations must be strengthened, while sanctions should
be better targeted, to make them "less harsh on innocent
populations, and more effective in penalizing delinquent rulers,"
Annan stressed.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general has recently announced the setup of a
special international panel to reevaluate the peace operations the
U.N. has taken in the past 50 years and find ways to better
functions in the next century. The panel is preparing a separate
report on the subject to be submitted to the Millennium Summit for
consideration.
</P>
<P>
On environmental issues, Annan called for a "new ethic of
stewardship" and a system of "green accounting" to ensure that
environmental costs and benefits are integrated into economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general sought commitments from nations to an
ambitious agenda, which includes that:
</P>
<P>
By 2015, people living in extreme poverty and the proportion
lacking safe and affordable water will be cut in half, all
children will be able to complete primary education and the gender
gap at all levels of education will be eliminated;
</P>
<P>
Within 10 years, HIV infection rates for persons 15-24 years
old will be reduced by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
By 2020, the lives of 100 million slum dwellers will be
improved.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the industrialized countries to grant free
market access for goods produced in poor countries, cancel all
official debts of the heavily indebted poor countries in return
for those countries making demonstrable commitment to poverty
reduction.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief strongly recommended that new information
technology play a major role in fighting poverty and promoting
human development as well as improving U.N. operations.
</P>
<P>
He announced setting up a network of 10,000 online sites to
provide medical information to hospitals and clinics throughout
the developing world, a consortium of high tech volunteer corps
called United Nations Information Technology Service (UNITeS) and
a disaster response initiative.
</P>
<P>
Annan also proposed an ambitious series of changes for the
United Nations itself, pointing to the expansion of its 15-nation
Security Council and the veto right of the five permanent member
nations.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the U.N. General Assembly designated its 55th session,
starting on September 5, as the Millennium Assembly and decided to
hold the Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
As part of the preparations for the gathering, five regional
hearings have been held to define the agenda.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior U.N. official, who declined to be
identified, the summiteers would be divided into four groups to
discuss a common agenda. A declaration is expected to be released
at the end of the three-day summit.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. expert believed that it is important to set clear and
well-defined goals for the summit, but what is more significant is
to follow up afterward. "Endless meetings and empty talks will
lead to nowhere," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
