<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottawa Valley Sees Gold Rush  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Ottawa Valley is seeing a gold rush
with local high-tech firms landing 233 million Canadian dollars (
about 161 million U.S. dollars) in venture capital for the first
three months of the year, the Ottawa Citizen newspaper said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Four deals to be unveiled later this month will add another 100
million Canadian dollars (about 69 million U.S. dollars) in new
venture capital investment.
</P>
<P>
The "seed investments" are impressive compared with last year,
when the region's entire industry attracted a total of 220 million
Canadian dollars (about 152 million U.S. dollars), according to
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The rapid influx of venture financing has made the national
capital region an investment destination accounting for 30 percent
of an estimated 800 million dollars (about 552 million U.S.
dollars) plus in new deals in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
That was second only to Toronto, the country's biggest city,
where high-tech firms attracted more than 35 percent of the total
estimated investment.
</P>
<P>
A large chunk of the fresh venture capital originates in the
United States, where 20 investors - mostly from the Boston and San
Francisco areas - contributed to the first-quarter flood of
investment in the Ottawa area, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The gold rush is a result of fierce competition between venture
firms, which have been busy targeting startups in the United
States for most of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
For the moment, outside venture capitalists are taking notice
of the Ottawa area, where competition is comparatively less with
dozens of startups already located to attract financing,
especially from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Venture capital firms are raising a record amount of new money
from investors eager to cash in on the high-tech boom. These
financial mercenaries are responding, in turn, to the exceptional
returns generated by those startups in high-tech niches from data
networking to fibre-optics.
</P>
<P>
They earn their money by investing in a high-tech firm during
its earliest stage, then selling their stake when the startup gets
bought by a larger player or goes public, said the newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
