<HEADLINE> Iran Urges International Cooperation Against Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Vice President for Executive
Affairs Mohammad Hashemi on Monday called on the international
community to join hands with the Iranian government in a campaign
against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to foreign envoys based in Tehran, Hashemi said Iran
confiscated over 253 tons of narcotics in 1999, including six tons
of heroin, 22 tons of morphine, 204 tons of opium, 18 tons of
hashish and three tons of others.
</P>
<P>
He said that during 1998 and 1999, a large majority of the
opium, heroin and morphine seizures had been made in Iran since it
borders the largest drugs producer in the world, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Hashemi said that Iran has taken effective steps to promote
bilateral and multilateral cooperation to universalize the anti-
drug campaign, including the opening of the office of the United
Nations Drug Control Program (UNDCP) in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, an effective campaign against the global
threat of drug trafficking needs more funds and equipment, which
Iran is not able to obtain alone.
</P>
<P>
Iran has taken necessary measures at the national level in the
framework of a national program of the year 2000 and has drawn a
multi-dimensional plan with a budget of 3,250 billion rials (about
1.08 billion U.S. dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
However, due to financial problems and limitations, the Iranian
government was only able to allocate 300 million dollars for the
plan, he added.
</P>
<P>
Iran is a main transit route for drugs smuggled from
Afghanistan, the world's largest opium producer, and neighboring
Pakistan to Europe and oil-rich Gulf Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Iran launched the strict anti-drug campaign in 1989 after the
Iranian Majlis or parliament passed an anti-drug law authorizing
capital punishment for drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
A commander of the Iranian security forces said last November
that the country had spent one billion dollars on combating drug
trafficking since the Islamic revolution in 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
