<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Seeks Oil Output Hike Without Harming Market: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar
Zanganeh said here on Monday that Iran seeks an oil output hike to
preserve its share in the world oil market but will not go for a
production rise which may ruin the market.
</P>
<P>
Iran is seeking a rise in oil production given the market
realities, Zanganeh stressed, adding its policy of not flooding the
market with additional oil does not mean that Iran will not
increase its production.
</P>
<P>
Refuting as baseless allegations that Iran is not able to
increase its oil production, Zanganeh said Iran has increased the
average oil production since the start of this month to preserve
its share in the world market.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister did not disclose how many barrels Iran
would add to its current output of about 3.3 million barrels per
day, the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
There should be timely supplies of crude oil to meet market
demand, he said, but there is no shortage of oil in the world oil
market in the first quarter of the current year. Therefore, oil
should not suddenly enter the market, he added.
</P>
<P>
Despite Iran and Iraq opposition, nine of the 11 members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) agreed in
Vienna at Tuesday to boost oil production by 6.3 percent, or a
total of 1.45 million barrels a day from April 1.
</P>
<P>
Iran initially did not sign the agreement, insisting that it was
a bow to U.S. pressure to bring down oil prices which almost
tripled since oil producers enforced an output curb in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran announced one day later that it would increase oil
production for fear of losing market share. Under Tuesday's
agreement, Iran should raise its oil production by 264,000 barrels
a day, thus enabling the cartel to boost total output by 7.5
percent over the ceiling set when it cut production last year.
</P>
<P>
Iran wants OPEC members to safeguard their long-term interests
and the survival of the cartel depends on the spirit of cooperation
and interaction among its members, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that OPEC members are fully independent and should
not make any decision under external pressure.
</P>
<P>
He said that from the economic point of view there was no need
to a single stage increase in production level, so Iran could not
accept such an irrational decision making.
</P>
<P>
He noted, however, that Iran believes in unity and consolidation
among OPEC member states and will strive to strengthen the
organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Africa-Europe Summit Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Monday urged African and European leaders to capitalize on
relationship of the past and to develop ties of the present.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak made the appeal in his inaugural speech at the first
Africa-Europe Summit that opened here Monday with an aim to forge a
new and strategic relationship between the two continents.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the changes and achievements made in Africa, Mubarak
said that Africa has witnessed during the past decade the efforts
to establish pillars of democracy, freedom, the respect for human
rights and the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed Africa should integrate itself in the economic
globalization and get along with the international changes.
</P>
<P>
"So the African leaders should take decisions for the
establishment of African federation programs and parliament," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He also hailed the declaration of the year 2000 as the year of
peace in Africa and called for the holding of the initial "
ministerial meeting in relation to security, stability, development
and cooperation in Africa."
</P>
<P>
Seven of the 15 EU members are former colonial powers in Africa
and the EU gives 15 billion U.S. dollars to Africa every five
years, more than any other single source.
</P>
<P>
Most African leaders hoped to exploit the summit to seek debts
reduction or cancellation, more financial aid and investment from
the rich Europe, their major creditor and trading partner.
</P>
<P>
The total external debts of African states reached 350 billion
dollars, with them spending 23 billion dollars, or 30.9 percent of
their exports to service the debt every year.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak in his speech called on the European creditors to help
ease the debt burden.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guetrres, whose country
initiated the summit and is holding the EU presidency, said in the
ensuing address "it is our profound wish that this most meaningful
occasion should represent a moment of renewal in the relationship
between our two neighboring continents."
</P>
<P>
Heads of state or government or their representatives from 66
African and EU states attended the two-day summit to discuss
political, economic and development issues in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
