<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marginalizing Africa "unacceptable": Portuguese PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Portugal's Prime Minister Antonio
Guterres warned on Monday that Africa is being marginalized in the
age of globalization.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed the marginalization of Africa is "unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Guterres made the remarks ahead of the first Africa-Europe
summit that opened Monday afternoon in the International Conference
Center in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The exports of the African countries accounted for 6 percent of
the world's total years ago, but the figure has declined to less
than 2 percent now, he added.
</P>
<P>
There is "a very urgent need" for Africa to integrate itself
into the global economy and Europe has "a major role" to play in
this respect, said Guterres, whose country is holding EU's rotating
presidency.
</P>
<P>
The Africa-Europe summit is opportune for the start of a
political dialog at the highest level, he said. And this is not a
mere historic conference, but the beginning of a continuous march,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The African and European sides have agreed on the formation of a
technical body to convene on a regular basis, the holding of a
ministerial meeting and organizing a second summit in 2003, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The international community must adopt an effective support
program that would open the markets of developed countries to the
exports of the poor states and transfer technology and investments
to them, Guterres said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
