<HEADLINE> India Aims to Manufacture 90 Pct of Defense Products at Home: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pathak, who was there to commission India's first home-made
fleet replenishment tanker, was quoted by the Press Trust of India
(PTI) as saying that his ministry has already taken steps to
modernize all the 39 ordnance factories in the country in a phased
manner in a bid to improve quality and production.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at the Indian East Naval Command in
Visakhapatnam that the production has been increased from 70
percent to 300 percent in some of the ordnance factories.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government had allocated a total of 12.41 billion
rupees (288.6 million U.S. dollars) for defense production in the
Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1997-2002), while in the 10th Five-
Year Plan period the figure is expected to be raised to 19 billion
rupees (441.86 million dollars), he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the PTI, the newly-built INS Atidya fleet
replenishment tanker, manufactured by Garden Rach Ship Builders
and Engineers Limited in Calcutta, is capable of fueling as many
as six ships at a time.
</P>
<P>
Pathak said that another tanker, INS Brahmaputra, would also be
handed over to the Western Naval Command this month. The shipyard
is also building two more submarines for the navy. 
</P>
