<HEADLINE> Call for Estrada's Resignation Fails to Gain Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Senate Minority Leader
Teofisto Guingona wrote President Joseph Estrada a letter on
Monday,asking him to step down "since the country is already in
disarray."
</P>
<P>
Guingona cited the lack of a sustained program of development,
the worsening unemployment situation, the continued depreciation
of the peso, and the bloodshed in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
However, the senator's call failed to gain support so far, even
from his own partymates in Lakas-NUCD.
</P>
<P>
In separate interviews, Senators Juan Flavier, Loren Legarda,
Robert Barbers and Rene Cayetano all stressed that Guingona's open
letter to President Estrada was not a party decision.
</P>
<P>
the Lakas senators said Estrada's resignation from his post is
not necessary, adding that the president should be given more time
to address the concerns raised by those discontented with his
leadership.
</P>
<P>
Senate President Blas Ople, on the other hand, advised Guingona
to seek psychiatric help, noting that his call for President
Estrada's resignation is a clear sign of "lapses" in his mental
health.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not saying Senator Guingona is stupid. I'm saying his
statement is," Ople said, as he questioned the wisdom of seeking
President Estrada's resignation when he was elected by an
overwhelming majority of the voting public in the 1998 polls.
</P>
