<HEADLINE> Recovered Cambodian Artifacts on Display </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The 122 looted pieces of arts
recently recovered from Thailand were on display Monday at the
National Museum as part of the Second National Culture's Day
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
The artifacts, pillaged from the 12-century-old Banteay Chhmar
Temple in northwestern Cambodia, included three heads of giant,
one garuda, one stone inscription and 117 pieces of base relief.
</P>
<P>
Thai authorities handed over the temple reliefs and other
artifacts to Cambodian officials at Poipet, the border town 350
kilometers northwest of Phnom Penh, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the Khmer Artifacts Exhibition, Sar
Kheng,deputy prime minister and minister of interior, called on
the whole nation to preserve and protect the national culture.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed to all departments involved with national
culture and patrimony not to cash in on these ancient temples, but
focus on the preservation and renovation of as many temples as
possible.
</P>
<P>
The recovered artifacts will be exhibited for about two months
as part of government's campaign to raise public awareness about
the need to stop the pillage of Cambodia's cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
Built between the 9th and 13th centuries, the ancient temples
are a symbol of Cambodian national pride and the country's biggest
tourist attraction. But looting and lack of security have damaged
the temples seriously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
