<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obuchi in Coma, Japanese Cabinet to Resign En Masse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese cabinet will most
likely have to resign en masse as Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi is
in a coma in an intensive care unit after suffering a stroke
Sunday, acting Prime Minister Mikio Aoki said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"At this point, it's difficult for the premier to make his own
decisions," Aoki told a press conference. "We will have to decide
what to do after considering his condition," he added.
</P>
<P>
A government source said the resignation would come within a
day or two.
</P>
<P>
Yoshiro Mori, secretary general of Obuchi's ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) and the party's No. 2 figure, is being
tipped as a possible successor to Obuchi, Kyodo News quoted LDP
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The LDP and its coalition partner, the New Komeito party, were
expected to complete the selection process for a candidate by the
end of the week, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi was taken to the private Juntendo University Hospital in
Tokyo at around 1 a.m. Sunday. He was later moved to the
hospital's intensive care unit after his condition worsened at
around 7:30 p.m., Aoki said.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the hospital put Obuchi on an artificial respirator
at 9:50 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The premier's blood pressure is stable, but his condition is
very unpredictable," the top Japanese government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Aoki, who was named as acting prime minister by the Japanese
government Monday morning, said he accepted the post because
doctors told him Obuchi would be unable to leave the hospital for
at least two or three days.
</P>
<P>
The government's announcement on Obuchi's hospitalization came
nearly a full day after it took place. His illness was initially
described as fatigue from overwork.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi's illness is certain to complicate Japan's political
schedule, including the timing of a general election for the House
of Representatives (lower house), which must be held by mid-
October.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, as prime minister, has the prerogative of dissolving
the lower house for an election. He was considering how timing of
such an action could work to his political advantage.
</P>
<P>
But illness is seen likely to limit his options, and makes it
difficult for him to lead a political scenario, political analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
As the acting prime minister could not dissolve the lower house,
so unless Obuchi returns to work or someone succeeds him
officially, the lower house will not be dissolved until its term
runs out in October, said an analyst.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi's hospitalization is also expected to have an impact
upon the Japanese government's preparations for the Group of Eight
(G-8) summit to be held in Okinawa in July.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi's prolonged illness could have an adverse effect on
Japan's economy if the current Diet (parliament) session is unable
to proceed smoothly to completion.
</P>
<P>
The fiscal 2000 budget has been already approved by the Diet,
but related spending measures must have Diet approval for the
appropriations to actually take effect.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi had been busy dealing with last week's eruptions of Mt.
Usu on Japan's northernmost main island Hokkaido.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Obuchi held talks with the leaders of the New
Komeito and the Liberal Party over the breakup of his tripartite
alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
