<HEADLINE> South Korea Sticks to One China Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Seoul, April 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
said Monday his country sticks to one China policy and will never
change it as Taiwan is an inseparable part of China.
</P>
<P>
The President made the remark here during a meeting with Zeng
Qinghong, head of the Organization Department of the Chinese
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
Kim also praised China for playing an important role in
maintaining peace and stability on the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Kim noted that the prospects for further developing South
Korean-Chinese ties will be much better as the two nations have
achieved a great deal in the fields of politics, economy, military,
culture and tourism since the establishment of diplomatic
relations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In response, Zeng spoke highly of South Korea's adhering to one
China policy and expounded the Chinese government's principle and
position on the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
China and South Korea have established cooperative partnership
oriented toward the 21st century in 1998 when President Kim Dae-
jung visited China, said Zeng, who is an alternative member of the
political bureau of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
Zeng, who arrived here for a four-day visit last Saturday at
the invitation of the South Korean government, has met South
Korean Prime Minister Park Tae-joon and other government officials
and political leaders.
</P>
<P>
Zeng will leave here for Tokyo tomorrow. South Korea is the
third leg of his Asia-Pacific region's visit, which has taken him
to Australia and New Zealand. 
</P>
