<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Reveals Upbeat Public Mood in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Results of the poll released Monday showed that 60 percent of
the respondents were satisfied with the present situation, higher
than the 44 percent recorded in a similar survey held in January.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether Hong Kong would continue to be prosperous
and stable, 71 percent said they were confident, up from 67
percent recorded in January.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more respondents (41 percent) than before (30
percent) expressed satisfaction with the overall performance of
the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
An HAB spokesman said the positive responses may have been
influenced by the generally well-received budget delivered just
before the survey period and other signs of economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
The survey also revealed that the three problems which were
mentioned most often, in the order of priority, were labor,
economy and education-related problems.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of people who worried about education has gone
up from 13 per cent in January to 18 per cent.
</P>
<P>
The survey is the 87th in the series. It was conducted by
interviewing over the telephone a total of 1,664 respondents aged
15 to 64 from March 13 to 17 in the evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
