<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Can Turkey's Coalition Trio Weather Crisis? by Huai Chengbo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit
is to hold a summit of his three coalition partners Monday in a bid
to cobble the shattering coalition after his bill on constitutional
amendment failed to be approved by the parliament last week.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Ecevit and Delvet Bahceli, the deputy prime
minister and chairman of the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP), will
ask Mesut Yilmaz, chairman of the Motherland Party (ANAP), the
coalition's junior partner, to make a last-minute appeal for his
deputies to vote in favor of the presidential amendment in
Wednesday's second voting.
</P>
<P>
In the first, secret voting Wednesday night, Ecevit's bill on a
constitutional change to allow President Suleyman Demirel, whose
single seven-year term expires on May 16 this year, to stay on for
a second, five-year term, only got 303 "yes" votes, far short of
the required minimum of 330 votes for an amendment to be
legislated.  The government's failure in parliament was blamed
mainly on a serious ANAP defection in the voting despite that the
coalition partners had agreed that they would back the bill.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts here are becoming more and more inclined to
believe that unless something dramatic happens in the next 48 hours
before Wednesday's vote, the bid ardently pushed by Ecevit is dead
and the real debate is whether or not the current coalition can
survive given serious confidence crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ANAP deputies who oppose Demirel will presumably remain
defiant and will not change their votes unless they are forced to
declare their preferences during the voting to the party leader, a
move which would violate parliamentary rules. The balloting for
constitutional amendment is handled in a secret way and parties are
not supposed to force their deputies to toe the party line.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, hopes that the main opposition Virtue Party (FP) will
make a last-minute U-turn and support the bill are vanishing. FP
leader Recai Kutan accused Ecevit over the weekend of neglecting
key problems at the expense of reforming the presidency.
</P>
<P>
The government tried to woo the FP by linking the Demirel vote
with another constitutional amendment that would make it harder for
parties to be closed down by the supreme court. The FP is currently
facing a closure case on charges of being a hub of anti-secular and
pro-fundamentalist activities.
</P>
<P>
The reformist wing in the FP has also made it clear that they
stand against any bargaining for the current constitutional
amendments with the government. They claim that if Demirel leaves
office, the winds of change and democratic reform will gain
momentum.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some opposition True Path Party (DYP) deputies are
obviously unwilling to let Demirel at the Presidential Palace any
longer, hoping that if the 76-year-old president returns home among
the DYP ranks, he may revamp the DYP and dismiss Tansu Ciller as
chairperson.
</P>
<P>
Thus, earlier predictions that most DYP deputies would vote for
Demirel are uncertain, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
Taking into consideration these factors, many observers have
come to realize that Demirel's departure from presidency is a
foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
Now all eyes are on Ecevit, who did some brain-storming during
his just-concluded four-day visit to India about the future of his
coalition, holds the key to the fate of the government.
</P>
<P>
There are widespread speculations that Ecevit and Bahceli might
be prepared to kick out ANAP and form a two-party minority
government with backing from Ciller's DYP.
</P>
<P>
There are also some allegations that some of ANAP deputies, who
are reluctant to leave the government, may be willing to defect and
join the MHP, thus bolstering the strength of a new government.
</P>
<P>
The two parties, whose popularity has been on the rise according
to recent public opinion polls, may also want to capitalize on this
and push for early elections.
</P>
<P>
Should the parliament fail to elect a president in four rounds
by May 16, it would be automatically dissolved and early elections
would be held within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
However, MHP Parliamentary Group Chairman Omer Izgi claimed
Sunday that he still believes that ANAP deputies and 100 FP
deputies will vote for Demirel on Wednesday and the constitutional
amendment package will have an easy ride winning more than 367
votes for it to become law immediately signed by the president.
</P>
<P>
But he could not explain why many MHP ministers in the cabinet
publicly stated that last week's vote had shown that "Demirel's
term in office will not be extended." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Not to Deploy Troops in South Lebanon: Cohen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States will not send
troops to fill the vacuum areas in south Lebanon after Israeli
soldiers withdraw by July, visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference after meeting with Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak Monday morning, Cohen also revealed that
no final decisions had been made about the future of any
international presence in the buffer area.
</P>
<P>
Even if U.N. peacekeepers would be sent to ensure the quiet
along the border between Israel and Lebanon, Cohen suggested, U.S.
soldiers will not participate.
</P>
<P>
Barak played down the idea of an international peacekeeping
force in the zone, which had been promoted by Israeli officials in
the past few weeks to guard against possible cross-border attacks
from south Lebanon on Israel's northern border communities after
its troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Barak clarified his stand on the issue by saying that the
expansion of U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL), if there is
such a plan, will not be significant.
</P>
<P>
The UNIFIL has been in the region since Israel's first invasion
of Lebanon in 1978. Israel officials had expressed hopes that the
force could be expended from its current defense areas to fill in
the zone vacated by Israel Defense Forces (IDF).
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-strong peacekeeping troops from nine countries
currently deployed primarily in the western and central sectors of
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Barak stated Monday that he didn't think that there was any need
for adding extra nations, which are not in UNIFIL now, to the
multi-national forces.
</P>
<P>
The statement excluded U.S. and France, who are not in UNIFIL,
from joining any future expansion of the international buffer
troops.
</P>
<P>
France, another pivotal side mediating between Israel, and
Syrian and Lebanon because of its historical links to the two Arab
counties, has agreed to send soldiers during French Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin's visit here last month, on condition of an peace
deal with Syria, the major power broker in Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Barak emphasized that the current size of UNIFIL is sufficient
for peacekeeping in the area as long as Lebanon acts to disarming
other militias in the zone. He was referring to Lebanese Hezbollah,
the Shiite Muslim militant group fighting to end the Israeli
occupation since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think there will be any problems (in dismantling
Hezbollah). If there will be a will, there will be a way to solve
the issue with UNIFIL under the auspice of U.N. Security Council,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Barak reiterated his pledge that he would withdraw Israeli
troops from south Lebanon by July, ending an 18-year Israeli
occupation.
</P>
<P>
Warning against possible heat-up in the northern border areas
after the July pullback, Barak said Israel is the strongest country
in the region and he doubted whether any country would attempt to
test its strength.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 15-kilometer-deep "security zone" in south
Lebanon in 1985 with a proclaimed aim of preventing cross-border
guerrilla attacks on its north. But mounting Israeli casualties
have spurred a growing public pressure for a pullout. 
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet on March 5 gave backing to Barak's pledge to
withdraw from south Lebanon by July, with or without a peace deal
with Syria or Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian talks, which resumed last December after a
45-month break, stumbled again in January over a dispute over the
fate of the Golan Heights, a strategic Syrian plateau seized by
Israel in the 1967 Middle East war. 
</P>
<P>
Some strategy experts believe Israel hopes the announcement of
possible unilateral withdrawal would make the Syrians lose their
last bargaining chip and force them to return to the negotiating
table. 
</P>
<P>
However, Israel's wishful thinking was dampened by Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad, whose summit meeting with U.S. President
Bill Clinton in Geneva on March 26 failed to produce any progress
as expected. The summit was once regarded as the last chance for
reviving the talks. 
</P>
<P>
To face this reality, Israeli leaders had to mull more seriously
than before about their plans to carry out the redeployment
unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, Israel has been seeking support from U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Clinton and the European Union (EU)
for the idea of deploying a multi-national buffer troops in the
vacuum areas or expanding the UNIFIL institution.
</P>
<P>
However, diplomats in Jerusalem said EU states are unlikely to
offer troops to join such an army unless there is a security
agreement with Syria to avoid the risk of bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
Finland and Ireland, who currently serve in the UNIFIL, had
signaled their intention of pulling out if it is expanded to the
whole security zone.
</P>
<P>
To add Israel's embarrassment, Lebanese Defense Minister Ghazi
Zuetir announced last Saturday to the effect that Beirut might ask
Damascus to send troops to south Lebanon in the event of a
unilateral Israeli pullout.
</P>
<P>
The suggestion later was rejected by Syrian Foreign Minister
Faruk Shareh, whose country deploys some 35,000 troops in Lebanon
since 1976.
</P>
<P>
To garner support from Washington, Barak raised the issue during
his meeting with Cohen, who made Israel as the first stop of his
annual trip to friendly states of U.S. in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Cohen arrived in Israel Sunday evening after a brief stop and
will also visit Jordan, Qatar, Bahrain, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, the
United Arab Emirates and Oman during his two-week tour.
</P>
<P>
One of Cohen's objectives of the multi-leg trip, according to
Israeli officials, is to examine how to build a broader security
network to enable Middle East allies to collaborate in countering
joint threats like terrorism and possible biological and chemical
warfare.
</P>
<P>
He also wanted to discuss with Israeli leaders military
cooperation between the two countries, the 17-billion-U.S.-dollar
U.S. defense assistance which Israel wants to accompany any peace
deal with Syria, and other security issues concerning the peace
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Police Continue Crackdown on Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish security forces on Monday
unearthed the bodies of four people killed by the radical Islamic
terrorist group Hezbollah in southeastern Diyarbakir province.
</P>
<P>
The excavations started after a Hezbollah member was captured in
Cinar town of the province and told the police that there were dead
bodies in an empty field in the area, the Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has launched a massive crackdown across the country since
last year on Hezbollah, which Ankara accuses of seeking to turn
overwhelmingly Muslim but secular Turkey into a strict Islam-ruled
country by resorting to violent and terrorist means.
</P>
<P>
During the day, nine Hezbollah members were also arrested in the
southeastern Gaziantep province.
</P>
<P>
They were charged with engaging in propaganda activities for the
terrorist group in mosques to recruit new members.
</P>
<P>
Two rifles, 25 discs, cassettes and books were seized during the
operations which were still underway in the region, said the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
