<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Doctor Develops Medicine for Prostate Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish doctor has developed a
kind of medicine which can kill cancerous prostate cells without
damaging the healthy tissues in the gland, the Anatolia News Agency
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The medicine, called Aptosyn (Exisulind), has been proved
effective in treating large intestines cancer as well, said the
inventor Rifat Pamukcu at the American Research Association's
Conference.
</P>
<P>
Pamukcu, who acts as the vice president of the Cell Pathway
Company in Pennsylvania, the U.S., said Aptosyn functions by
reducing the androgen receptor concentration and eliminating the
effect of cancerous cells.
</P>
<P>
Aptosyn causes the cancerous cells to commit suicide and
therefore eradicates them without harming the healthy tissues in
the prostate, the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
The results of clinical tests on people will be announced during
the American Urology Congress to be held in Atlanta on May 1.
</P>
<P>
Pamukcu said the medicine had been tested on 96 patients, whose
prostate cancer recurred following a prostate operation.
</P>
<P>
Cell Pathway has applied to the U.S. Health Department for
permission to use Aptosyn on patients who also suffer from large
intestines cancer.
</P>
<P>
The medicine which is currently studied by the U.S. Health
Department, can soon be used in treating polyposis on patients with
large intestines cancer, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
