<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Polio Case Detected in Western Pacific for 3 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Western Pacific Region has not
reported any new cases of indigenous poliomyelitis for three
consecutive years, the biggest landmark on the road to
certification of the region as free from poliomyelitis.
</P>
<P>
This was declared here Monday by Shigeru Omi, Regional Director
of the World Health Organization (WHO) Western Pacific Region.
</P>
<P>
"This is a tremendous achievement for all countries of the
region,"Omi told the 10th meeting of the WHO Western Pacific
Regional Technical Advisory Group on the expanded program on
immunization and poliomyelitis eradication held from April 2 to 3.
</P>
<P>
Countries of the region are very confident that they are not
missing any poliomyelitis cases because over 18,000 children with
acute flaccid paralysis have been investigated during the last
three years, yet no indigenous poliovirus has been detected.
</P>
<P>
The Regional Certification Commission, an independent body
whose eight members were also present at the meeting, will have
the ultimate responsibility to decide whether the Western Pacific
Region can be certified as poliomyelitis-free later this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
