<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-nine secondary
schools in Malaysia's capital city of Kuala Lumpur will form crime
prevention clubs to educate students against criminal activities,
Bernama news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The clubs would educate students on crime prevention measures
for their safety, Kuala Lumpur Police Chief Kamarudin Mohamed Ali
was quoted as saying after launching the second crime prevention
campaign here.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the clubs in collaboration of the Kuala Lumpur
Crime Prevention Foundation and the Youth and Sports Ministry in
other schools has effectively reduced crime activities in schools,
the police officer said.
</P>
<P>
He said that last year, there were 39 cases in Kuala Lumpur
involving students including five cases with secret society
elements.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 secondary students in Kuala Lumpur with disciplinary
problems such as fighting, smoking and obscenities, but not
gangsterism, would undergo counseling and motivation session
programs by the Foundation and the Education Ministry, the police
officer said. 
