<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Unfazed Over Increasing Foreign Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Monday that the country's increasing foreign debt stock will
enable the government to manage public expenditure more wisely and
to gain access to cash resources to fund its pro-poor programs.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Spokesman Jerry Barican stressed that this "
therefore augurs well for public expenditure management in terms
of lower cost of domestic borrowing and the availability of cash
resources for budgetary purposes."
</P>
<P>
As of December 31, 1999, the country's foreign debt amounted to
52.2 billion U.S. dollars, or about 65 percent of the GNP(gross
national product), which is six percentage points lower than the
1998 level, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"There is thus an improvement in the country's capacity to pay
its debt," Barican pointed out in a statement.
</P>
<P>
According to Barican, the "increase in magnitude from the 1998
level of 47.8 billion dollars by 9.2 percent is explained by the
significant increase in bond flotations by the public sector."
</P>
<P>
He said the rise in budget deficit in 1999 prompted the
government to avail of relatively cheaper foreign money in order
to beef up its available cash resources.
</P>
<P>
This strategy, Barican said, enabled the government to generate
a buffer against any unforeseen financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"It also puts the government in a position to contain any
upward pressure against the low prevailing cost of domestic
borrowing," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman assured the public that the government does
careful programming and observes judicious releases of budgetary
allotment in accordance with the annual appropriation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
