<HEADLINE> E. Africa Threatened by Severe Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The threat of starvation in
parts of eastern Africa is severe with nearly 16 million people in
need of emergency food assistance, South African Press Association
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Pastoral areas, including southeastern Ethiopia, northern Kenya
and several parts of Somalia, are particularly affected due to
successive years of poor rains with loss of large numbers of
livestock, a report released by the United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is the hardest hit with more than eight million people
at risk, while in Kenya nearly 2.7 million people are facing
severe food shortage, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Poor rainfall is forecast in the Sub-Sahara region for the
current season, so the number of people in need of assistance is
anticipated to increase," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It said that "only a massive international effort in the coming
months in support of these populations can avert further human
suffering and loss of life."
</P>
<P>
The Great Lakes region is also reported to be facing a massive
food supply shortage due to civil strife, insecurity, shortage of
inputs and erratic rainfall.
</P>
<P>
In Mozambique, it is estimated that 1.9 million people are
affected by the flood disaster. Major losses of crops and
livestock are sustained in the southern and central provinces of
Maputo, Gaza, Inhambane, Manica and Sofala.
</P>
<P>
In Madagascar, heavy rains and high winds from two consecutive
cyclones caused destruction to property and infrastructure and
left some 10,000 people homeless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
