<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho government
announced on Monday that it will establish a special commission to
investigate the disturbances in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The country's acting Prime Minister Kelebone Maope told the
National Assembly that the commission will consist of three judges
of the Lesotho Court of Appeal, according to a report by South
African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
The commission will undertake an in-depth investigation into
the causes of the disturbances from July to November 1998 and find
out who were the instigators of violence, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has appealed to everyone who knows
anything about the disturbances to cooperate with the commission
in order that the truth be exposed.
</P>
<P>
The commission is expected to start its investigations on April
25 and complete its work within a month and a half, he said.
</P>
<P>
In May 1998, the Lesotho Congress for Democracy overwhelmingly
won the third general election since Lesotho won independence in
1966. However, the opposition parties resisted the election
result, causing serious disturbance in the tiny southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
Some parts of Maseru, capital of Lesotho, and the southern
district town of Maseteng were destroyed by fire, with government
vehicles hijacked and business closed down. 
