<HEADLINE> International Meeting of Free Trade Union Opens in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The 17th conference of the
International Confederation of Free Trade Union (ICFTU) opened in
South Africa's port city of Durban on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony at Duban International
Convention Center, South African Deputy President Jacob Zuma said
"the conference takes place at a time when we are poised between
the old and the new and the people of the African continent are
keenly looking forward to the continued development of a more
humane and socially just society on the continent."
</P>
<P>
The world is "witnessing truly epochal shifts in the very
rubric of society", including the technological advances which are
"reshaping our universe in such profound ways," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of people living in absolute poverty has
increased, concomitantly with an increase in wealth of the
developed nations and the astronomical fortunes accumulated by
individuals, Zuma noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that globalization can not be left to manifest
itself through the globalizing of poverty, instead of the
spreading of wealth across the globe.
</P>
<P>
"This is a state of events that is potentially disastrous not
only for the poorer nations, but also for the rich nations. The
side by side existence of extreme poverty and immense wealth, in
the long term, in the 'global village' means that instability will
increase in society as the poor majority fight for better
conditions rather than succumb to continuous poverty," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that urgent action is required to end the conflicts
around the world and counter the effects of the spread of
HIV/AIDS, particularly on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Zuma noted that another debilitating matter that continues to
impact negatively on the common development potential of the world
is the issue of debt relief.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to draw the attention of the trade unionists from the
developed world to the protectionist practices that continue to
exist in many of the developed countries, despite calls to open up
markets to the developing nations on favorable conditions," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
