<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Zone Records 3.8 billion Euro Trade Deficit in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The 11-country euro zone
registered a trade deficit of 3.8 billion euros (some 3.65 billion
U.S. dollars) with the rest of the world in January this year, up
280 percent over a year ago, the European Union's statistical
office, Eurostat, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the initial estimate of the EU's external trade for
January 2000 was a deficit of 12.3 billion euros (some 11.8
billion dollars). In January 1999, the 15-nation bloc recorded an
external trade deficit of 6.8 billion euros (about 7.9 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The deterioration of trade balances in both the euro zone and
the EU as a whole is explained by imports growing faster than
exports in 1999, with import rising by 9 percent and export by 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The estimates for January indicate that the renewed growth in
exports that began in June last year is continuing.
</P>
<P>
According to the Eurostat, the European Union's exports were
weak in all main product groupings except "Chemicals" and "Energy,
" while for imports there was growth in all groupings except "Food
and drinks and "Crude materials."
</P>
<P>
The oil price increase during 1999 was reflected in a 26
percent growth in the value of energy imports, with the energy
deficit increasing by 13 billion euros (about 13.8 billion dollars)
.
</P>
<P>
Euro zone countries include Belgium, Germany, Spain, France,
Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and
Finland. The four EU member states not in the single currency zone
are Britain, Sweden, Denmark and Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
