<HEADLINE> British Columbia Orders End of Strike by School Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The legislature of Canada's
province of British Columbia passed a bill late Sunday to force 12,
000 school employees, who have been on strike for one week, back
to work.
</P>
<P>
The strike has left 370,000 students from spring break still
out of public schools, media reports here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It was important in the public interest that we act and we've
acted and children will be back in school," Premier Ujjal Dosanjh
of the province was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The premier called a rare Sunday sitting of the legislature
after the Public School Employers' Association failed to reach an
agreement with the Canadian Union of Public Employees on pay
equity, long-term disability and job security.
</P>
<P>
While ordering an end of the strike, the legislation also
called for the continued efforts to negotiate a resolution of
hundreds of convoluted issues.
</P>
<P>
Provincial Labor Minister Joy MacPhail was to appoint an
industrial inquiry commissioner to help the two sides reach a deal
in two months.
</P>
<P>
If there is no agreement by then, the commissioner will
recommend binding arbitration within 15 days, according to the
reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
