<HEADLINE> Japan's Acting PM Plays Key Role in Tripartite Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary
Mikio Aoki, who was appointed acting prime minister Monday
following Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's sudden hospitalization, is
known for his close ties with the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP)'s
two coalition partners, the Liberal Party (LP) and the New Komeito
party.
</P>
<P>
Aoki, 65, is a key member of Obuchi's faction in the (LDP),
which launched a tripartite coalition government with the LP and
the New Komeito, an alliance that lasted only six months.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi announced Saturday that his LDP and the New Komeito are
ending their partnership with the LP, the smallest of the three
coalition partners, after he and the leaders of the other two
parties failed to share basic ideas on how to operate the
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Aoki, who concurrently heads the Okinawa Development Agency, is
an old friend of LP leader Ichiro Ozawa and had been expected to
play a key role in propelling the tripartite coalition under
Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
Aoki, who succeeded Hiromu Nonaka as chief cabinet secretary
and top government spokesman last October, is serving his third
consecutive term in the House of Councilors, or the upper house.
</P>
<P>
He is a close aide to former Japanese Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita. After helping Takeshita's election campaigns while
still a student at Waseda University, Aoki became secretary to him.
</P>
<P>
After serving in his native Shimane Prefecture as a prefectural
assembly member for five terms, Aoki advanced into Japan's
national politics by being elected to the upper house in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Following the 1998 upper house election, Aoki became secretary
general of the LDP delegation in the upper chamber.
</P>
<P>
By winning cooperation from the New Komeito in passing a number
of key bills at the last regular Diet (parliament) session which
ended in August 1999, Aoki further boosted his reputation.
</P>
<P>
Aoki said Monday he decided to accept the post of acting prime
minister based on the assessment that Obuchi would not be able to
return to work briefly.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, 62, was hospitalized early Sunday after suffering a
stroke and is being treated in an intensive care unit at a Tokyo
hospital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
