<HEADLINE> FIA International Court of Appeal to Hear McLaren Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Automobile
Federation opened its International Court of Appeal here on Monday
to hear McLaren's protest over the disqualification of its driver
David Coulthard in an earlier Formula One race.
</P>
<P>
In the March 26 Brazilian Formula One Grand Prix, Coulthard
placed second behind Ferrari's Michael Schumacher but was
disqualified when stewards ruled the front wing of his car was two
millimeters out of tolerance.
</P>
<P>
McLaren argued that the "very bumpy" track contributed to the
car being out of regulation. He added that the car was clearly in
regulation at the beginning of the race.
</P>
<P>
FIA spokesman Francesco Longanesi said the panel would announce
its decision Tuesday. If the appeal fails, F1's top team the last
two seasons will be without a point in either the drivers' or
constructors' standings after two races.
</P>
<P>
The court of appeals consists of FIA Chairman Philippe Roberti
de Winghe and judges from the Netherlands, Portugal, Ireland and
Spain.
</P>
<P>
Five months ago, an FIA appeal panel seemed to bend the rules
by reinstating Ferrari's 1-2 finish in the Malaysian Grand Prix
after stewards ruled aerodynamic deflectors were out of compliance
by one centimeter. That took the meet victory and the season
title from McLaren's Mika Hakkinen and forced the title to be
decided at the season-ending Japanese Grand Prix. Hakkinen won in
Japan and claimed the drivers' championship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
