<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Stone Age Started Earlier Than Previously Thought: Experts ( 1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Asia's Stone Age started as early
as 800,000 years ago, putting it at a similar level to those in
Africa and Europe, experts with a Sino-American archeological team
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was based on the Sino-American joint
excavation launched in 1993 in the Baise Basin, in south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, which neighbors Vietnam. Large
numbers of stone tools including two-sided stone hand axes were
unearthed during the excavation.
</P>
<P>
"The Baise project has been the earliest, the largest and the
most reliably dated Stone-Age excavation so far found in East Asia,
" said Richard Potts, an archeologist from the Human Origins
Program of the Smithsonian Institute in Washington DC.
</P>
<P>
The previously most reliably dated stone tools in East Asia
were no more than 500,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
"The tools provide compelling evidence to refute a concept
originated by Harvard University anthropologist Hallam Movius in
1948," said Potts.
</P>
<P>
Movius is generally respected as one of the most influential
theorists on paleoanthropology. In one of his most famous theories,
he divided the peoples of the Early Stone Age into two groups:
those who could make sophisticated, two-sided stone hand axes and
those who could not.
</P>
<P>
According to his early research, he wrote off the entire Asian
continent to the second class, saying that Asians were less adept
compared with people in Africa and Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, thousands of stone tools dating back some 800,000
years ago have been unearthed in the 800-sq-km basin, which is a
hilly rural area covered with red dirt. Most of the stone tools
were so systematically manufactured that experts believe some 50
working procedures must have been taken to polish each one of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Stone Age Started Earlier Than Previously Thought: Experts ( 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The hand axes were symmetrically forged, and all are of a
similar size, which reflect the fairly high level craftsmanship of
the time, said Potts.
</P>
<P>
Huang Weiwen, an archeologist with the China Institute of
Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology under the Chinese
Academy of Sciences, told Xinhua that the toolmakers were as
skillful as their counterparts in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Asians and Africans living in the early period of the Stone
Age shared the same level of technology," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the stone relics were collected as early as 1973.
However, archeologists had found it hard to date some of them.
</P>
<P>
It was not until recently that Alan Deino, a geologist with the
Berkeley Geochronology Center in California, used radiometric
decay of argon isotopes to pinpoint the age of tektite, which is a
glassy remnant of molten rocks, in the tools.
</P>
<P>
Geologists here have suggested that a large meteorite struck
the South China region about 800,000 years ago. The impact sent up
a spray of molten debris and ignited fires that cleared a thick
cover of trees and exposed red earth as well as the underlying
beds of large conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
After the catastrophe, early humans had plenty of stones for
making tools. The tektite resulted from the meteorite impact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
