<HEADLINE> Libyan Leader Meets EU Commission President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi met
here with European Union Commission President Romano Prodi Monday
on the fringe of the upcoming Africa-Europe summit that will open
later in the day.
</P>
<P>
The Gaddafi-Prodi talks, taking place by Gaddafi's spacious tent
erected in the presidential palace, is the Libyan leader's first
such meeting since U.N. sanctions on Libya were suspended last year
after the Northern Africa state surrended the two suspects in a
1988 bombing of an American flight.
</P>
<P>
No details of the meeting are available now. But Irish Prime
Minister Bertie Ahern, who emerged from the palace after his own
talks with Gaddafi, said the Libyan leader's talks with Prodi were
significant.
</P>
<P>
A Belgian delegate to the summit has said earlier that Prodi and
Gaddafi would be likely to discuss Libya's possible participation
in the Barcelona process, a political and economic dialog begun in
1995 between the EU and countries of the Mediterranean rim.
</P>
<P>
The leaders came to Cairo for the first Africa-Europe summit,
which will be held on Monday and Tuesday, involving heads of state
or government, or their representatives from most of the 53 African
states and all the 15 EU members.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day conference, the leaders will address
political, economic, development issues in the poor Africa
continent. 
</P>
