<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plummet On Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Share prices took a hammering on
Singapore Stock Market Monday as sentiment of caution was
prevailing over the market on lack of no positive news.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index dropped 60.91 points, or 2.86
percent, to close at 2,071.68 points, falling through the 2,100-
point psychological support level.
</P>
<P>
The market volume totaled 268.92 million shares worth 615.31
million Singapore dollars (358.78 million U.S. dollars). Declining
issues overwhelmed advancers nearly 10 times at 301 to 35 with 187
counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
MAE Engg topped the volume list as it registered a turnover of
35.73 million units. It was followed by SingTel which had 14.78
million shares transacted. NOL was the next with 10.33 million
counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Parkway led ascent of the day edging up 16 cents to close at 5
Singapore dollars. First Eng moved up 12 cents to finish at 1.07
Singapore dollars. Natelect inched up 10 cents to end at 11.3
Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
PacCent was the biggest loser of the day plummeting by 310
cents to close at 20.00 Singapore dollars. SPH 100 incurred a loss
of 190 cents to finish at 26.00 Singapore dollars. Creative 50
gave up 180 cents to end at 52.50 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brokers attributed Monday's drop to lack of positive factors to
spurn the market following the continual fall on the NASDAQ last
week.
</P>
<P>
They singled out the SingTel which fell by five percent to 2.32
Singapore dollars on a sell-off following Singapore's full
liberalization of its telecommunication market starting on April 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted that Singapore Stock Market's capitalization has
sank by almost 20 percent from its January 3 peak as investors
ignored heavyweights and blue chips in favor of relatively
lightweight technology plays.
</P>
<P>
They said the market sentiment was heavily dampened by the
sharp fall on the NASDAQ whose electronic index plunged by 390
points or 7.87 percent last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
