<HEADLINE> Nigerian Lawyers to Find Way Out of Sharia Controversy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian lawyers Sunday decided to
send a panel to dialog with the country's Zamfara State government
over its controversial way of implementing the Islamic legal
system Sharia.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, on Monday reported
that the Nigerian Bar Association (NBA) described at one of its
meeting in Lagos on Sunday the amputation of Baba Zangedi by
Zamfara State government last week as "inhuman".
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed that NBA should pay a private visit to Zamfara
State to meet the Attorney-General of the state, the Chief
Executive, Governor Ahmed Sani, Chief Judge and possibly members
of the House of Assembly with a view to seeing how those issues
can be amicably and democratically resolved," said NBA spokesman,
George Igbokwe.
</P>
<P>
"On Sharia issue, we took a decision condemning the amputation
of somebody's hand in execution of a court judgment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the widespread condemnation, Governor Ahmed Sani of
Zamfara State, who took the lead in the west African country in
January this year to introduce Sharia, had vowed to amputate more
in order to implement Sharia to full extent.
</P>
<P>
He declared last week that any civil servant who stole more
than 4,000 naira (about 40 U.S. dollars) public fund would
henceforth have his right hand amputated.
</P>
<P>
After the bloody conflicts over Sharia in Kaduna and other
States, President Olusegun Obasanjo had expressed hopes in
different occasion that such private organizations like the NBC
should play roles in finding a way out of the issue, which the
government was not in a good position to intervene. 
</P>
</TEXT>
