<HEADLINE> New Party Formed in Japan to Stay Within Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Former Japanese Home Affairs
Minister Takeshi Noda and 25 other lawmakers Monday split from the
Liberal Party (LP) and formed a new party, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to continue to take responsibility as members of
the coalition government," Noda was quoted as saying at a meeting
in announcing the launch of the new party.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the 50 Diet (parliament) members of the LP
joined the meeting, according to Kyodo.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, LP leader Ichiro Ozawa did not express any clear
decision on pulling his party out of the coalition at a party
meeting Monday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Ozawa was widely expected to announce his party's withdrawal
from the coalition in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi announced last Saturday
that his Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and the New Komeito party
will end their alliance with the LP.
</P>
<P>
"We failed to share basic ideas over how to operate the
coalition government," Obuchi told reporters after meeting with
Ozawa and New Komeito leader Takenori Kanzaki Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
The LP formed a two-way coalition with the LDP in January 1999,
which was joined by the New Komeito in October of that year.
</P>
<P>
In the 15 months the LP was in the coalition, Ozawa had
threatened to pull his party out on several occasions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
