<HEADLINE> Those Responsible for Major Guangdong Fire Dealt With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, April 3 (Xinhua)-- Three leading officials of
Longjiang Township of Huilai County in southern Guangdong Province,
where a major fire occurred last month, were removed from their
posts after being held responsible for the disaster.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made by the Party committee and government of
Jieyang City, which exercises administration over Huilai County.
</P>
<P>
The three local officials are Huang Xianliang, who acted as the
Party secretary of Longjiang Township, Wu Mubo, the township head,
and Tang Longqing, the deputy township head.
</P>
<P>
Also in line with the decision, the Party committee and
government of Huilai County should make a thorough review of the
fire and seek the responsibility of Li Qin, who is deputy head of
Huilai County and is in charge of safety in production.
</P>
<P>
Xie Xiguang, head of the Huilai Fire Brigade, was also
suspended from his duties and is awaiting further investigation.
A special police team was formed to track down Chen Linping, who
is director of the ill-fated Jiacheng Lighter Factory and is still
a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, the accident occurred around 3:40
p.m. on the afternoon of March 28 and was caused by the leakage of
inflammable gas and an ensuing explosion, killing 17 people and
injuring six others. The fire was put out around 5:00 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The lighter factory is an overseas-funded firm that did not
have prior registration with the relevant local industrial and
commercial administrative departments, and it came to the town of
Longjiang in Huilai County from Humen in the nearby city of
Dongguan early this year. The unlicensed factory, which employs
more than 100 workers, mainly produces disposable plastic lighters.
</P>
<P>
After the accident, local government officials, along with a
fire brigade, public security officers, and medical workers,
rushed to the site promptly for rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
While urging relevant departments to go all out to save the
injured and try their best to reduce the death toll, Guangdong
Provincial Party Secretary Li Changchun called for a serious
investigation of the disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
