<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Development in Western China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The central part of the Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia region has proven
gas reserves of 230 billion cu.m. and new gas-bearing structures
are constantly being discovered, according to the China National
Petroleum Corp (CNPC).
</P>
<P>
The eastern part of Sichuan Province in southwest China has
verified gas reserves of 200 billion cu.m., while natural gas
reserves in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region total 160 billion
cu.m.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a large gas field in northwest China's Qinghai
Province has verified reserves of 50 billion cu.m.
</P>
<P>
The CNPC source said that China plans to double its gas
production capacity to 30 billion cu.m. by the year 2005, the
majority of which will come from the Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia region,
Sichuan Province, and Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
Also, Ningxia is developing a thermal power production base
with installed capacity topping 10 million kilowatts, and Shaanxi
plans to expand its coal production capacity and installed power
capacity to 100 million tons and 10 million kilowatts,
respectively. Priority will still be given to the terraced
development of hydropower at the upper reaches of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Along with conventional energy development, the western region
will continue to pay close attention to developing the new and
renewable energy sources including geothermal and wind and solar
to optimize the structure of energy consumption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Development in Western China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China is shifting its energy
development focus from east to west as it undertakes massive
exploration and utilization of natural gas in the western region
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The west, including the provinces of Shaanxi, Gansu, Sichuan,
and Qinghai, the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region and Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, is very rich in oil, gas, coal, and hydropower.
</P>
<P>
The central and local governments have issued preferential
policies for developing the energy industry in this region, and
energy there has maintained an annual increase rate of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Today, the energy sector accounts for about 50 percent of west
China's industrial output value, according to the China Energy
Research Society (CERS).
</P>
<P>
The CERS experts say that optimization of industrial structure
and increasing demand for energy and raw materials in the eastern
region of the country has stimulated energy development in the
west.
</P>
<P>
Through years of development, China has developed three large
natural gas production bases in the Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia region,
the Tarim Basin, and Sichuan Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low Scientific Level Hinders Western Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior official has said that
the present level of science and technology in the western part of
China could not provide proper support for a leap forward in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The official with the Ministry of Science and Technology said
that one major factor hindering development of the western region
is the low level of its scientific and technological development.
</P>
<P>
He said a joint research project launched by his ministry and
government departments concerned indicated that the scientific
infrastructure facilities in the western provinces and autonomous
regions are quite outdated. In addition, many scientists and
researchers are eager to find posts in the developed coastal areas,
as many western region research institutions do not have enough
funds and have not built up a market-oriented personnel system.
</P>
<P>
He said the western region does not have badly needed
agricultural technology and seed varieties for developing high-
quality and high-efficiency agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The joint research project also showed that skills of farmers
need to be greatly improved, and the building of agrotechnology
and personnel markets needs greater efforts in the region.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the lack of scientific and technological exchange
channels hinders the efforts of the western region to fully
utilize the scientific discoveries made by the coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
As to scientific research organs, he said, a major problem is
that most of them have not arranged any market-oriented research
programs. Moreover, most ventures in the western region have not
yet built up an innovation mechanism that can respond quickly to
market changes.
</P>
<P>
The pollution emitted by rural enterprises and the upgrading of
state-owned enterprises also require more efforts by scientists
and technicians.
</P>
<P>
He said scientific feasibility studies are also badly needed
for future large projects in the western region, as many projects
completed in the past have not brought the expected profits and
have even produced adverse side-effects as a result of a lack of
rational planning.  
</P>
</TEXT>
