<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China's Poverty Line System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The guarantee of a minimum
standard of living is the last social safety net in China's social
security system.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Civil Affairs of China has listed four
categories of urban poor as beneficiaries of the poverty line
system: those with no regular income, no ability to work and no
one to support; families with incomes below the minimum standard
of living; the unemployed no longer covered by unemployment
benefits policies; and others whose living standards are below the
poverty line.
</P>
<P>
China's old social security system, which was founded in the
1950s, has provided a small portion of the population with a
minimum standard of living.
</P>
<P>
China's 40-year-old social security system was patterned on
that of the former Soviet Union, with expenditures solely funded
by the state and state-owned enterprises regardless of the country
's financial health.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Shanghai took the initiative by implementing the
system of a minimum standard of living, and the practice quickly
spread to the rest of China.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Guangdong Province extended the this safety net not
only to all cities, but also to its rural areas.
</P>
<P>
By September last year, all 668 cities and 1,638 towns where
county seats are located have been covered by the system of a
minimum standard of living, and more than 2.817 million city
residents were receiving subsidies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Soldiers Armed With Intranet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- In a barracks of the Chinese
People's Liberation Army (PLA), Sergeant Yuan Hucheng is talking
with his young pals about what type of arms the Taiwan troops are
equipped with.
</P>
<P>
By clicking the mouse, Yuan pulls up pictures of aircraft,
tanks, and frigates of the army across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
"The 'army net bar' helps us learn about the armed forces of
other countries and regions in an easier way," Yuan says, "It was
unimaginable before."
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, Chinese soldiers and officers are becoming armed and
acquainted with a new weapon and friend -- the PLA Intranet.
</P>
<P>
PLA headquarters has been working hard building its internal
information network to give PLA troops access to on-line libraries,
lectures, mail, and even movies, as the General Political
Department of the PLA has opened a on-line cinema for the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
According to one officer, many PLA soldiers are now able to
cyber-surf download, and write with Chinese input, and some are
even becoming good at creating multi-media software, he says.
</P>
<P>
"With the computer network, grassroots soldiers and officers
are experiencing enormous changes in their way of thinking," says
Dong Gushun, a political commissar of a PLA division. "Along with
the popularization of the Intranet, the Chinese army has entered
into a new stage of development."  
</P>
</TEXT>
