<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economist Suggests New Ways for Developing West (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A leading Chinese economist
suggested recently that western China must initiate new ways for
future development to suit the fundamental changes in the internal
and external economic situation.
</P>
<P>
The west should rely on markets instead of preferential
policies made by the central authorities, Chen Jiagui, vice-
president of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS), said
in an essay in the latest issue of the China Industrial Economics
journal.
</P>
<P>
The western municipality of Chongqing, and all western
provinces and autonomous regions should actively cultivate their
own markets and encourage all sectors of the economy including the
state-owned, collective, and private, the well-known economist
said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, people in the west must change the former
extensive mode of economic development into an intensive one,
which will greatly save both natural and human resources.
</P>
<P>
Shifting the focus from traditional mineral exploitation, the
west should pursue coordinated development of all industries, with
emphasis placing on high-yield farming and farm produce processing,
electronics, information technologies, automation, space
technologies, and tourism-related services, Chen suggests.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Chen urges local governments to stimulate township
enterprises as this will provide many more job opportunities for
surplus workers in the west.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of small towns and the development of township
enterprises also should be combined, Chen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
