<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economist Suggests New Ways for Developing West (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's central authorities are planning an ambitious project
to enhance the economic strength of the western region to
harmonize the pace of development between the economically-
retarded west and the comparatively developed east.
</P>
<P>
With 56 percent of the country's land area and 23 percent of
its population, the west encompasses 10 provinces and autonomous
regions and Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
The west also has half of China's total mineral reserves.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that from 1949 to 1978, the average annual
growth of the west reached 7.25 percent in terms of gross national
product, slightly higher than that of the east.
</P>
<P>
However, after the 1980s, the Chinese government decided to
open the east and coastal areas to the rest of the world,
gradually widening the gap between east and west.
</P>
<P>
Adjacent to Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan, the east easily
attracts much more overseas investment and exports more goods.
</P>
<P>
Chen urged the west to earnestly analyze the new conditions
prevailing in domestic and foreign markets, and thereby project
their own development strategies.
</P>
<P>
The regional governments should underscore safeguarding the
environment and raising living standards, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to sources, the central government this year will
focus on infrastructure construction and environmental protection
in western China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
