<HEADLINE> ADB, Bangladesh Sign Poverty Reduction Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
Monday signed a partnership agreement with Bangladesh on poverty
reduction here.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by ADB President Tadao Chino and
Bangladesh Finance Minister Shah A. M. S. Kibria on behalf of
their respective sides.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will facilitate future ADB financing for poverty
reduction, which was declared as the overriding goal by the ADB
recently.
</P>
<P>
The ADB started signing poverty reduction partnership
agreements separately with its developing member countries, of
which Bangladesh became a model as it was the first to implement
the bank's strategy.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Bangladesh will strive to achieve
universal primary education by the year 2010 and reduce the
maternal mortality rate by 75 percent and the infant mortality
rate by 65 percent.It will also aim to cut the proportion of
malnourished children under five by 40 percent and make
reproductive health services available to all women of appropriate
age by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Chino said the ADB lending to Bangladesh will be about 500
million U.S. dollars annually from next year. The bank's annual
lending to the country at the moment is around 362 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
When meeting with Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, the
visiting ADB president praised the government's micro-credit
policy,particularly the poverty alleviation program.
</P>
<P>
Hasina welcomed the ADB chief and urged him to consider the
objective situation of a country while pushing for any reforms.
</P>
</TEXT>
