<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Import 400,000 Tons of Sugar in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is likely to import 400,
000 tons of Sugar in 2000 to bridge the gap between production and
consumption, an official source disclosed here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The government has received final figures of 2.5 million tons
of sugar production from the country's sugar mills, against the
local consumption of 2.9 million tons, an official from the
Ministry of Food was quoted by the Associated Press of Pakistan as
saying.
</P>
<P>
To meet the shortfall, the country will have to import
approximately 400,000 tons of sugar through the private sector
this year, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Sugar producers in Pakistan have been urging the government to
increase sugar import tariff substantially so that imported sugar
does not price out the indigenous product.
</P>
<P>
Sugar price is currently some 9 rupees (17 U.S.cents) per
kilograms in the international markets, much lower than that in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian country has produced 46 million tons of
sugarcane in 1999-2000, compared with 55 million tons a year ago,
official statistics show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
