<HEADLINE> Nigeria Opens Border to Cameroon Despite Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Despite a dispute between Nigeria
and Cameroon over the ownership of the oil-rich Bakassi Peninsula
on their border, Nigeria's Cross River State has reportedly
concluded a trade agreement to throw its border open to Cameroon.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, reported on Monday
that the Cross River State and Cameroon had agreed at a meeting
over the weekend at Bodam, a boundary town in the Francophone
nation, to construct link roads between their border towns to
facilitate trade relations and movement.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the state, which has land and sea borders with
Cameroon, was quoted as saying that the inter and intra-boundary
linkages would create markets and development for both countries.
</P>
<P>
Some border roads listed for construction in the budget had
been approved by the state's House of Assembly, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cameroon and Nigeria have fought several wars for the ownership
of Bakassi. The two countries are currently involved in a
prolonged legal battle at the International Tribunal of Hague over
the ownership of the peninsula. 
</P>
