<HEADLINE> Nigeria Plans Another Military Purge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government is planning
to down- size its armed forces in an effort to professionalize
them, according to a report reaching here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Defence Minister Theophilus Danjuma said at the weekend that
the government is poised to carry out the reorganization of the
armed forces to meet the yearnings and aspirations of Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner in honor of visiting United States Defense
 Secretary William Cohen in the capital Abuja, Danjuma said the
forthcoming down-size exercise of the armed forces is imperative
if democracy must succeed in the country.
</P>
<P>
Danjuma expressed the government's appreciation to the U.S.
government for its promise of 10 million U.S. dollars for various
training programs of Nigerian military aimed at making the forces
truly professional.
</P>
<P>
The proposed purge of the armed forces would be the third since
the inauguration of the present government last May. The first
such exercise affected mainly officers who were holding political
positions, while the second move involved those who held forte as
personal assistants or military assistants to their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, the first ever U.S. defense secretary to visit Nigeria,
said the U.S. government is committed to assisting the western
African country in its efforts to revamp its economy and
professionalize its armed forces, adding that "though Nigeria is
going through a very difficult time, at the end of the tunnel,
there would be light." 
</P>
</TEXT>
