<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Sturgeons Released into Yangtze River Found in East China Sea (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Fishery Bureau under China's
Ministry of Agriculture confirmed today that the "strange fish"
caught by a fisherman last month in the East China Sea was one of
the young Chinese sturgeons released into the Yangtze River last
year.
</P>
<P>
An bureau official said this indicates that some of the young
sturgeons released in Yichang in central China's Hubei Province on
December 28, last year, have successfully reached the sea after
swimming more than 2,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, a fisherman named Chen Fushun in
Zhejiang Province caught a live "strange fish" on March 17 which
had a metal plate on its back inscribed with the name of the
Yangtze River Aquatic Resources Institute and a telephone number.
</P>
<P>
When Chen got ashore the next afternoon, he phoned the
institute, which is in the city of Jingzhou in Hubei Province.
However, the two sides failed to understand each other because of
the great difference in their dialects.
</P>
<P>
Chen then took the fish to a market for sale only to be nabbed
up by the local police, who then sent the fish to a fish-breeder's
pond, but the fish died after 24 hours. Later, experts checked and
verified that the fish was one of the 100,000 young Chinese
sturgeons released into the Yangtze River at the end of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Sturgeons Released into Yangtze River Found in East China Sea (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liu Zheng, head of the Wild Life Protection Division of the
Fishery Bureau, said that finding the sturgeon in the sea proves
that releasing artificially bred Chinese sturgeons into the
Yangtze River is an effective way to prevent the extinction of the
rare fish.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese sturgeon is known as a living fossil since it is
one of the oldest vertebrates in the world. The rare fish migrates
to the Jinshajiang River, a tributary of the Yangtze, from the sea
and spawns there, and when the minnows grow to about 10 cm, they
migrate back to the sea some 3,000 km away. As adults, they
migrate back upstream to their birthplace.
</P>
<P>
But the fish now faces worsening living conditions,
environmental pollution, and illegal and rampant fishing.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the number of Chinese sturgeons that swim back
to the Yangtze River every year has dropped to less than 1,000,
with only some 500 of them able to spawn. They warned that the
fish may become extinct in 50 years if effective measures are not
taken immediately.
</P>
<P>
To save the endangered species, China has set up two large
bases in Hubei to breed the fish, including the Yangtze River
Aquatic Resources Institute, and from 1983 to 1998, nearly six
million Chinese sturgeon minnows were released into the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
However, the minnows' survival rate is very low, as they are
mostly less than 10 cm in length and usually fall prey to other
species of fish in the river. To increased the survival rate, 100,
000 young Chinese sturgeons measuring over 10 cm were released
into the Yangtze last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quality of China's Vegetable Seeds Needs Improvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China has world's largest area of
vegetable cultivation, growing most vegetable varieties. However,
the qualified rate of the vegetable seeds is only 57.8 percent,
according to a recent selective examination.
</P>
<P>
The spot check, conducted by the State Bureau of Quality and
Technical Supervision (SBQTS) among 45 kinds of Chinese cabbage
and kale seeds from 33 seed companies across China, showed that
only 26 kinds were up to standard.
</P>
<P>
The qualified rate of Chinese cabbage reached 68.9 percent, and
the ratio for kale was only 37.5 percent. Seeds of state-owned
enterprises were found to be of higher quality than those of
private companies, the examination revealed. The major quality
problems include germination and low purity.
</P>
<P>
China has a vegetable cultivation area of about 6.9 million
hectares, and vegetables are a major part of the Chinese diet.
Incomplete statistics show that the country has several thousand
seed companies, and over 60 percent deal in vegetable seeds.
</P>
<P>
SBQTS officials said that after China's entry into the World
Trade Organization, Chinese seed enterprises will face much
stiffer competition, and must increase the quality of their seeds.
</P>
<P>
The bureau and Chinese agricultural departments will to
penalize enterprises which fail to meet state standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Seen Leading Regional Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Citibank and Salomon Smith
Barney sees Malaysia as having a very prominent place in the
forefront of regional acceleration recovery, helped by a
supportive international environment.
</P>
<P>
The Citigroup estimates Malaysia's GDP growth at around 6
percent this year and 7 percent next year, up from 5.4 percent in
1999, Citibank and Salomon Smith Barney Director David Simmonds
said Monday at a press briefing on "Market Opportunities Around
Asia Recovery."
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's recovery would be led by increased domestic demand,
particularly private consumption, and not by the net export sector,
with growth in domestic demand forecast at 12.8 percent this year
and 13 percent next year, said Simmonds, who is also an Asia
currency strategist.
</P>
<P>
Private consumption in Malaysia was forecast to grow by 6.8
percent this year and 7 percent next year, compared with 2.5
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said the international environment is quite positive and
supportive of further acceleration in regional and Malaysia's
growth this year.
</P>
<P>
The Citigroup forecast the inflation rate in Malaysia, which
was 2.8 percent in 1999, will rise to 3 percent this year and 3.5
percent next year.
</P>
<P>
It also forecast Malaysia's current account as a percentage of
gross domestic product (GDP) to decrease to 10.8 percent in 2000
and 5.8 percent in 2001 as against 13.9 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Given that there is no real significant issue in inflation and
no adverse development in international and regional markets, the
Asia currency strategist saw no immediate change in monetary
policy in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He spoke positively of Malaysia's ringgit peg to the U.S.
dollar adopted in September 1998, saying the peg has been quite
helpful and provided an environment that benefits exporters who
are not challenged or excessively challenged from a competitive
point of view and exports could forge strongly ahead.
</P>
<P>
The peg allows the government to pursue policies that it feels
are positive, Simmonds said, adding that although capital controls
see Malaysia pursuing a different path to recovery from the others,
they have not taken Malaysia into a different alley where recovery
is concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
