<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Indonesian President Questioned Over Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Attorney General's
Office Monday questioned former President Soeharto over alleged
corruption,collusion and nepotistic practices during his 32-year
rule.
</P>
<P>
The questioning took place at his residence in Central Jakarta
but was suspended due to medical reasons.
</P>
<P>
The investigation team was chaired by Head of the Directorate
for Political Intelligence at the Attorney General's Office
Purnama Munthe with five members.
</P>
<P>
The team was joined by an independent medical team while
Soeharto, 78, was accompanied by his eldest daughter Siti
Hardiyanti Indrarukmana, lawyers and doctors.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after one and half hours of questioning,
Munthe said the investigation had not yet completed and therefore
no result could be announced. "We will announce such a result when
it (investigation) is completed."
</P>
<P>
He said the investigation was suspended due to medical reasons.
</P>
<P>
"Based on the doctors' advices, the examination was ceased
because(during the examination) Soeharto's blood tension arose. We
will continue our investigation if the doctors give us the green
light to do so," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Soeharto's lawyer Juan Felix Tampubolon said his
client was examined in connection with the foundations he chaired,
namely, the Foundation of Dakab, Supersemar and Dharmais.
</P>
<P>
He said the probe was suspended due to medical reasons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Supardi, a member of the independent
medical team, said: "In the course of the examination, Soeharto
was exhausted and his blood tension went up. So we advised the
prosecutors to stop questioning. Because if it (questioning) was
continued it would endanger the health of Soeharto."
</P>
<P>
The questioning was carried out after Soeharto ignored a third
summons to appear at the Attorney General's Office Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Soeharto twice defied a legal summons to show up at
the Attorney General's Office for questioning about alleged
corruption in the charities he used to control, citing poor health.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was named as a suspect in a case of alleged corruption
during his 32-year-rule after Attorney General Marzuki Darusman
decided to reopen the case in December last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
