<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Official Warns Against Tech Stocks Frenzy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Deputy Prime Minister
Lee Hsien Loong struck a cautionary note Monday about investors'
recent mania in pursuing Internet-related stocks in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a closed-door seminar organized by the Monetary
Authority of Singapore (MAS), Lee advised investors to "shift more
toward an investment rather than a punting mentality."
</P>
<P>
He said few fully understand that they have to take
responsibility for their own investment decisions and accept the
risks along with the upside.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately this is only brought home when the market
crashes,or when problems surface," he said.
</P>
<P>
The dotcom mania in Singapore is much milder, Lee said, but
Singaporeans are also carried along by the general enthusiasm for
Internet-related stocks.
</P>
<P>
Although the Singapore government hopes to prevent the dotcom
enthusiasm from getting out of hand, he said, it can not go back
to merit regulation, namely, regulating by judging business merits.
</P>
<P>
"The surest form of investor education is to get burnt. But we
hope the lesson if it comes will not be too painful," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
