<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China-funded Chrome Mine in South Africa Operating Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A chrome mine and a ferro-chrome
smelter in South Africa funded by China Iron and Steel Industry
and Trade Group Corporation (CISITGC) is expected to produce 300,
000 tons of chrome ore and five tons of ferro-chrome this year.
</P>
<P>
Dong Zhixiong, vice-president of the CISITGC, told Xinhua that
his company and the Northern Province Development Corporation in
South Africa set up a joint venture -- ASA Metals (Pty.) Ltd.-- in
1996.
</P>
<P>
With an investment of 70 million U.S. dollars, the joint
venture is the largest funded by China in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture, with a term of 40 years, is designated to
develop a chrome mine which currently produces 400,000 tons of
chrome ore annually and can be mined for 100 years.
</P>
<P>
The venture also includes a ferro-chrome smelter with a
designed annual production capacity of 200,000 tons of charge-
grade ferro-chrome.
</P>
<P>
Since the joint venture went into operation in 1997, the chrome
mine has made profits for three consecutive years, ending its 20-
year history of loss making, according to Dong.
</P>
<P>
Dong said that the output of chrome ore has exceeded 900,000
tons, and sells well in China as well as in Europe, the United
States, and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The first phase project of the ferro-chrome smelter has
exported over 20,000 tons of ferro-chrome to Japan, the United
State, and the European markets since it became operational in
August last year. So far this year, 80 percent of its output has
been ordered.
</P>
<P>
Dong said the joint venture is a win-win project for both sides,
adding that it greatly eases the shortage of chrome ore in China,
and at the same time, the Northern Province in South Africa for
the first time has its own deep-processing enterprise which turns
out high value-added products, while providing employment for 500
local people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
