<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China's plan to celebrate the
centennial of the discovery of the Dunhuang Caves caught
nationwide newspapers headlines this week.
</P>
<P>
-- China to Celebrate Centennial Discovery of Dunhuang Caves
</P>
<P>
China's Ministry of Culture announced on March 28 said it plans
to celebrate the centennial of the Dunhuang Caves, exhibiting
replicas of stolen treasures for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Together with the Gansu provincial government and the State
Administration of Cultural Heritage (SACH), the Ministry of
Culture will organize centennial celebrations in July, featuring a
commemorative meeting, relic exhibitions, art performances, and
tourist activities to mark the discovery of 50,000 items of
Buddhist documents and other relics.
</P>
<P>
-- 1,300-year-old Tombs Found in Shaanxi
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists in northwest China's Shaanxi Province have
excavated 75 relics from two ancient tombs dating back to the Tang
Dynasty (618-907).
</P>
<P>
The finds include bronze mirrors, earthenware articles, and
ancient seals in the tombs near the city of Xianyang.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists said these relics enrich our knowledge of
ritual traditions during the Tang Dynasty, and will be invaluable
for further research.
</P>
<P>
-- Zhejiang Museum Organizes Exhibit of Masterpiece Paintings
</P>
<P>
The Zhejiang Museum has begun showing painting masterpieces by
some of the country's most famous painters, including Huang
Binhong, Wu Changshuo, Xu Beihong, and Lu Xiaguang.
</P>
<P>
The first group of exhibits include paintings, calligraphy,
seal cuttings, and poems created by Wu Changshuo.
</P>
<P>
The museum is collecting treasured relics by these masters in
order to accumulate a large art collection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Archaeology News: Weekly Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region recently vowed to well
protect ancient relics during the process of westward development.
</P>
<P>
The regional government plans to take protection measures for
the famous Niya and Loulan ruins, and will also speed up repair
works at other heritage sites.
</P>
<P>
-- Neolithic Sites Experimentally Excavated
</P>
<P>
Some Neolithic sites near Luoyang in central Henan Province
have been excavated on an experimental basis.
</P>
<P>
Cultural relics from earthenware to stone tools were found by
local archaeologists after they dug an area of 90 square meters, a
tiny part of the total site of 20,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists said they have also unearthed four tombs
dating back thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
-- 2,200-year-old Wall Sections Primarily Restored
</P>
<P>
The Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region announced they have
basically restored some destroyed sections of the Great Wall
constructed during the Qin Dynasty (221 B.C. - 207 B.C.)
</P>
<P>
Local relics protectors used 10,000 cubic meters of stone
material to repair the 300-meter-long broken wall section.
</P>
<P>
The regional government is preparing further repair work for
another wall section and a beacon tower, located in deep in the
Yinshan Mountains.
</P>
<P>
-- Shandong Police Recover Stolen Paintings
</P>
<P>
Police in Qingzhou in east China's Shandong Province recently
recovered 12 paintings stolen by a local farmer.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the portrait paintings from the Ming Dynasty (1368
- 1644) have high artistic and research value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
