<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures: Poverty Lines in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Facts &AMP; Figures: Poverty Lines in
China:
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1999, a total of 2.81 million urban residents
received subsistence security allowances across China.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the composition of the recipients, those who have
no ability to work, no source of income and no one to support them
account for one-quarter, while the employed, those laid-off from
state-owned enterprises, the unemployed and retired workers, and
others living in poverty, account for three-quarters.
</P>
<P>
Subsistence security standards, or poverty lines, are set by
local governments in accordance with their respective expenditure
levels on basic daily necessities, financial capabilities, and
other factors, and thus vary from place to place.
</P>
<P>
The poverty lines of 36 major cities in China (including
municipalities directly under the central government, provincial
capitals, and cities with separate budgets from the central
government) stand roughly as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- Shenzhen has the highest subsistence standard, 319 yuan (39
US dollars) a month, followed by Xiamen at 315 yuan, Guangzhou 281
yuan, Shanghai 280 yuan, Beijing 273 yuan, and Tianjin 241 yuan;
</P>
<P>
-- The cities of Dalian, Haikou, Hangzhou, Ningbo, Ji'nan, and
Qingdao also have a standard of over 200 yuan ( 24 US dollars) per
month.
</P>
<P>
-- The rest has the standards below 200 yuan, of which those
for Huhhot, Nanchang, and Yinchuan are the lowest at 143 yuan (17
US dollars).
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the regulations of the State Council, almost
all local governments have incorporated the funds for subsistence
allowances into their budgets. In 1999, a total of 1.969 billion
yuan was paid in subsistence allowances from the state and local
revenues, including a central government subsidy of 400 million
yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killing of Germans Simply a Criminal Case: Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Local police said today that the
slaughter of a German family in the early hours of Sunday in
Nanjing, the capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, is a simple
criminal case without any ambiguous background.
</P>
<P>
The Germans, who were awakened when four local farmers broke
into their residence, called the No. 8 Villa House, Jinling
Imperial Garden, were stabbed to death fighting with the burglars,
the police said.
</P>
<P>
All four suspects were caught on the spot by the police, who
rushed to the scene upon receiving a report from guards at the
residential area. The four have confessed to the robbery and
killings.
</P>
<P>
The attack was random, and did not specially target foreigners,
according to police.
</P>
<P>
The German victims include 51-year-old Juergen Pfrang, deputy
general manager of Yaxing-Benz, a Sino-German automotive joint
venture in the city of Yangzhou in Jiangsu Province, and his wife,
son and daughter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
