<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- A moderate aftershock measuring 4.5 on the Richter scale,
jolted Adapazari province in Turkey's Marmara Sea region on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The aftershock was centered on Sapanci township of the province,
felt in Istanbul and other neighboring provinces and causing
residents out to the streets from their homes in panic.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two aftershocks measuring 4.7 and 4.2 on the Richter
scale, were recorded in southern Kahramanmaras province.
</P>
<P>
The region was hit by a devastating 7.4-magnitude earthquake
last August.
</P>
<P>
Sabah (Morning):
</P>
<P>
-- Recep Onal, Turkish state minister in charge of economics,
said on Sunday that "at the end of the third year of our economic
program, we will reach the EU's economic criteria."
</P>
<P>
He said that the program, starting from last year, should be
assessed at the end of June this year, adding that lowering the
chronic high inflation is still a priority in the country.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- The Turkish-Greek Friendship and Cooperation Fair will be
organized in the Greek capital of Athens between April 20-23, in
which a total of 90 Turkish companies are expected to take part.
</P>
<P>
The fair was described as a significant opportunity to further
improve the latest rapprochement between the two countries.
</P>
