<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai, Pakistani Leaders Vow to Boost Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Pakistani leader General
Pervez Musharraf and Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai Monday
agreed to strengthen relations and boost cooperation between their
countries.
</P>
<P>
During Monday's meeting at the Government House, the two
leaders discussed broad issues covering bilateral ties and
relationship between Pakistan and the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN), according to Thai Government Spokesman
Akapol Sorasuchart.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders were pleased to see that the Pakistani-Thai
relations have kept growing during the last 50 years and they
vowed to explore new areas for bilateral cooperation, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are now planning to celebrate the 50th
anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Musharraf, who is on a five-nation Southeast Asia tour,
reiterated Pakistan's strong wishes to seek ASEAN support and
develop economic, trade and financial cooperation with ASEAN
countries.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN made Pakistan a "sectoral" dialogue partner in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Pakistani-Indian relations, Thai Prime
Minister Chuan appealed for the relaxation of tension in the South
Asian subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his concern about the case of Pakistan's
former Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and hoped Pakistan would handle
the case fairly.
</P>
<P>
Musharraf said he has left the case to the court and "
everything will be open and fair."
</P>
<P>
Thailand is the last stop of Musharraf's regional tour, which
began on March 26 and which has taken him to Malaysia, Singapore,
Indonesia and Brunei.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani leader arrived here Sunday and will return to his
country Monday evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Corporate Bond Market Expected to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The corporate bond market in
Malaysia is expected to record a robust growth of 20 to 30 percent
in the next two years, a market observer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
For the market to grow, the interest rate should be low and
there should be the recognition of long-term capital needs and the
efficiency of bonds, David Zezza, Deutsche Bank managing director
for Asian Local Markets, said at a one-day conference here on the
development of the local debt market.
</P>
<P>
"There should be a shift in the allocation of capital in the
banking sector to the bond market while fixed income must serve as
a global asset allocation tool," he said while presenting a paper
at the conference jointly organized by the Hong-Kong based
magazine Financial Asia and Rating Agency Malaysia Bhd (RAM).
</P>
<P>
He also urged regulators to seek a high degree of foreign
participation in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
He said that besides the benefit of increased capital inflow,
local investors would benefit from the opportunity to diversify
credit exposure, without having to take on foreign exchange risk.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, Malaysia's Finance Ministry Advisor Mustapa
Mohamed announced in his keynote address that for developing the
domestic corporate bond market, the Malaysian government is taking
several measures, including amending the framework for the bond
market, implementing a share registration system and establishing
a centralized clearing and settlement system for all bonds.
</P>
<P>
All the measures are aimed at helping prevent excessive
concentration of credit risk in the banking system, increase
resistance to contagion and systemic problems in the corporate and
financial sectors, improve investment efficiency and promote
healthy competition, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
