<HEADLINE> Indian Leaders Send Congratulatory Telegrams to Mark Ties With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Indian President Kocheril Raman
Narayanan and Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee have recently
sent congratulatory telegrams to their Chinese counterparts Jiang
Zemin and Zhu Rongji respectively to mark the 50th anniversary of
the establishment of the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"India and China are close neighbors. We greatly value the
spiritual and intellectual interaction between our two great
peoples and civilizations over the last two millennia, which has
enriched us both," said Narayanan in his message to President
Jiang on April 1.
</P>
<P>
"We have jointly bequeathed Panchsheel -- the Five Principles
of Peaceful Co-existence -- to the world, which at the dawn of the
new millennium has acquired new relevance in the conduct of inter-
State relations," the president added.
</P>
<P>
In his telegram to Chinese Premier Zhu on March 31, Vajpayee
said that "the twin imperatives of peace and prosperity impel us
to build on our historical affinity and expand our contacts and co-
operation."
</P>
<P>
With the joint efforts of the two sides, the two countries
could build a stable relationship of constructive cooperation into
the 21st century and contribute to peace and stability in Asia and
the whole world, Vajpayee added.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Indian Foreign Minister Jaswant Singh also sent a
congratulatory telegram to his Chinese counterpart Tang Jiaxuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
