<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Exhibition, Seminar Mark Basic Law Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 3 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition and seminar
marking the 10th anniversary of the promulgation of the Basic Law
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) opened here
today.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Jiang Enzhu, director of the Liaison Office of
the Central People's Government in the Hong Kong SAR, highly
praised people from all walks of life for their earnest effort in
carrying out the Basic Law over the past years.
</P>
<P>
Facts show that the Basic Law complies entirely with the
situation of Hong Kong and the interests of all the Chinese people
including the Hong Kong compatriots, and it is full of vitality,
said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Basic Law, which is cornerstone of the
political and legal systems of the Hong Kong SAR, offers legal
basis for the SAR administration and helps consolidate and further
develop the legal system of the region.
</P>
<P>
As the first law dedicated to the "one country, two systems,"
the Basic Law of the Hong Kong SAR has helped the smooth return of
Macao and will set an example for the ultimate reunification of
the motherland, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the young people are future backbone of the
community and it is important to acquainted them with the Basic
Law.
</P>
<P>
The active promotion of the Basic Law by the youth
organizations in Hong Kong has helped increase exchanges and
cooperation in the legal field between Hong Kong and the mainland
and has contributed much to the popularization of the Basic Law
among the young people, he said.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition and seminar was sponsored by the Hong Kong-based
Wen Wei Po newspaper and some youth organizations. Officials and
scholars from Hong Kong, Macao and the mainland delivered speeches
at the seminar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Tourists to China Surge in First Two Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The latest statistics from the China National Tourism
Administration indicate that in January and February the number of
overseas tourists jumped 13.86 percent over the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, the number of strictly foreign tourists surged 24.
8 percent to 1.27 million, with tourists from Asia and Europe
growing by 28.8 percent and 21.9 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Among the 15 major target countries, tourists from Republic of
Korea shot up 51 percent, while the increase in the number of
tourists from the Philippines, Russia, and Indonesia exceeded 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
Tourists from Hong Kong and Taiwan still played a major role of
the country's international tourism market. In the first two
months, the number of tourists from Hong Kong grew 11.6 percent to
9.07 million, and the number from Taiwan rose by 19.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the two months, international tourism revenues increased 17.
5 percent over the corresponding period last year, with spending
by tourists staying at least one night in China brought in 2.02
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
A tourist official attributed the rise of international tourism
mainly to the surging number of tourists from Hong Kong and Taiwan
who returned to the mainland for the traditional Spring Festival,
and foreign tourists who wished to experience the festive period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
