<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sarid's Security Further Heightened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Security around Education
Minister Yossi Sarid has been further tightened amid fears for the
the Meretz leader's safety.
</P>
<P>
Israel's internal security organization, the General Security
Service (GSS), has replaced Sarid's standard government-issued
Volvo with an armoured version and increased the number of guards
around him and his Tel Aviv home.
</P>
<P>
The decision to switch Sarid's car had been made just before
Shas spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef made his infamous speech
two weeks ago, security sources said.
</P>
<P>
But they added that the Rabbi's rantings did contribute the
decision to further increase the protection around Sarid and his
family.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Rabbi Yosef compared Sarid to Haman and Amalek,
two historical enemies of the Jews, and called for his memory to be
stamped out.
</P>
<P>
One week later, Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein ordered a
police probe of Yosef, indicating Shas spiritual leader may have
violated the 1948 Prevention of Terrorism Law banning
pronouncements that encourage violence.
</P>
<P>
Shas said on Sunday that Yosef will not agree to be interrogated
by police and will instead present a detailed clarification letter
to the investigators.
</P>
<P>
The cloud of crisis continued to loom over the government
coalition till now as Sarid vehemently rejected a proposed
compromise put forth by Prime Minister Ehud Barak over duties to be
delegated to Shas Deputy Education Minister Meshulam Nahari.
</P>
<P>
Sarid informed Barak during their meeting on Sunday that he is
unwilling to reopen the issue of a recovery program for Shas's
educational network, which faces a financial shortage of millions
of U.S. dollars due to poor management.
</P>
<P>
The proposed compromise, worked out by the Minister in the Prime
Minister's Office Haim Ramon, suggests transferring the auspices
for the Shas educational network to a special committee chaired by
Nahari and the education ministry director-general. Any decision
pertaining to the network will have to be approved by the two, with
Sarid having the final say on any unresolved issues.
</P>
<P>
In addition, according to the proposal, a special ministerial
committee including Sarid, Ramon would be formed to identify
problems and disputes connected to the educational network and to
stop them from erupting into further coalition crisis.
</P>
<P>
Barak is scheduled to hold more meetings with Sarid and Shas
leaders in the coming days in order to defuse the coalition crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
