<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Strives to Develop Corporate Bond Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is making efforts to
develop the domestic corporate bond market, an alternative to debt
financing, to help prevent excessive concentration of credit risk
in the banking system.
</P>
<P>
Rationalizing the importance of having such a market, Mustapa
Mohamed, advisor to the Finance Ministry, said Monday that a well-
developed bond market would also increase resistance to contagion
and systemic problems in the corporate and financial sectors,
besides improving investment efficiency resulting from an increase
in market-based allocation of capital and the providing of an
early warning system.
</P>
<P>
Besides enabling a diversification of risks away from the
banking sector, a well-developed bond market will also provide
healthy competition, thereby reducing the cost of funds and
helping raise the quality of financial services to corporate
borrowers, he said at a conference on the development of the local
debt market here.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, the government is finalizing amendments to
the Companies Act 1965, Securities Commission Act 1993 and the
Banking and Financial Institutions Act 1989 to effect the
government's decision on all approvals for debt issuance to be
centralized at the Securities Commission (SC), he said.
</P>
<P>
The amended framework for the corporate bond market, within
which corporate bond issuance is regulated, will come into effect
in the second half of this year, the advisor said.
</P>
<P>
He said the SC would also implement a share registration system
this year to allow issuers who meet certain criteria the
flexibility of raising multi-bond issues and timing them
accordingly to market conditions.
</P>
<P>
The advisor stressed the need to establish a centralized
clearing and settlement system for all bonds.
</P>
<P>
Bank Negara (State Bank) Malaysia has created the Bond
Information Dissemination System, from which listing and trading
information of all government and corporate bonds could be found,
he said, adding that the next step would be to develop it into a
centralized trading system and make it accessible to a bigger pool
of investors.
</P>
<P>
Mustapa also saw the necessity for the establishment of a bond
futures market as a subsequent step to expanding the bond market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African States to Harmonize Investment Code </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the East African
Community (EAC) treaty are to have a uniform investment code by
December, 2001, the East African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania recently held a seminar on
harmonization of investment code in Kenya's capital Nairobi,
evolving an ambitious timetable under which the three are to
prepare and adopt the code.
</P>
<P>
The code, when working, is expected to harmonize and
rationalize incentives in the trading bloc, especially those
related to taxation of industries.
</P>
<P>
Last November, the three nations launched the EAC treaty in
Arusha, a northern town in Tanzania, which failed to address the
critical issues of trade barriers that affect investment.
</P>
<P>
With a view to producing a model investment code by December
2001, the region is expected to be developed into a single market
and investment area.
</P>
<P>
The investment code to be adopted is to include guidelines on
investment policies, and address such issues as establishment and
functions of investment promotion agencies, guarantee of foreign
exchange, stabilization of trade laws, settlement of disputes and
incentives, among others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
