<HEADLINE> Sale of Tanzanian Bank Results in Retrenchment of Most Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- About 70 percent of the
workers of Tanzania's largest commercial bank will be sacked
following the sale of the bank to a South African company last
week, the regional East African weekly newspaper reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Employers of the National Bank of Commerce (NBC) of Tanzania
have been told by the new owners of the former state bank, the
Amalgamated Banks of South Africa (ABSA), that some 733 out of a
total of 1,100 workers must be retrenched, about 350 of them
"soon".
</P>
<P>
Although ABSA promised before purchasing NBC that it would
retain and re- train the staff and equip the bank with the latest
banking technology, it seems to be backtracking on its promise
hardly a week after taking it over on March 31, the report said.
</P>
<P>
ABSA, a controversial owner of the former state bank, last week
paid 15 billion Tanzanian shillings (18 million U.S. dollars) for
purchasing 70 percent of the shares. The Tanzanian government
still retains 30 percent of the shares.
</P>
<P>
With the privatization program of more big state institutions
to be implemented in the next 18 months, analysts said more than
7,000 Tanzanians may be retrenched. 
</P>
</TEXT>
