<HEADLINE> Angola, Belgium to Combat Gem Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government and the
Antwerp's High Council on Diamonds of Belgium have signed an
accord to combat gem trafficking and to create "transparent
control of the diamond trade", according to an official statement
reaching here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said that the accord followed the visit to
Angola in March by Belgian Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Louis
Michel and the issuance of a U.N. report on the violation of the
sanctions against the Angolan rebels in which Belgium was accused
of being one of the violators.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, new certificates of origin and importation
will be implemented to allow the immediate identification of
diamonds.
</P>
<P>
According to figures revealed by the Angolan government, the
country's parallel diamond market produced some 563,000 carats of
diamonds, valued at 140 million U.S. dollars, in the first half of
1999. 
</P>
