<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 46 Harbor Seals Return to Ocean Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- After swimming around the ship
twice, 26 baby harbor seals have returned to their ocean home,
following a group of 20 that returned to the water last month.
</P>
<P>
The 46 harbor seals were rescued by Chinese fishermen in
northeast China's Liaoning Province when they were abandoned by
their parents in February.
</P>
<P>
The baby seals, about one month old, were left on seashores and
ice floes, but were soon taken to a shelter especially opened for
them. Twenty of the seals were released in early March when the
floes melted, and the rest stayed for some health reasons.
</P>
<P>
To further arouse people's awareness of animal protection, the
Chinese Ministry of Agriculture and relevant departments of the
Liaoning Provincial government held a special ceremony for the
returning seals.
</P>
<P>
Harbor seals are under intensified national care and protection
in China. They live in the bay near Liaoning in the winter time
and give birth to their young on the ice floes.
</P>
<P>
There used to be more than 10,000 harbor seals in the Bohai Bay
near Tianjin Municipality, and the Yellow Sea in east China.
Harbor seals are endangered as their number has dropped
drastically to some 1,000 because of hunting in the past two
decades.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
