<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Candy Man's Sweet Mission (1)  by Gao Haiping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Like his late father, Zhang Chaohe
has shot to fame by titillating the tastebuds of countless locals
and tourists with probably the biggest, busiest candy counter in
China.
</P>
<P>
Every day, hundreds of people queue at his counter at the
Beijing Wangfujing Department Store. As the customers almost
completely ignore the 12 women sales clerks standing beside him,
he has to jump around, arms waving, like a football goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
Some people don't come to buy: They just want their children to
see this living legend among sweet-sellers. "Look!" they say to
their youngsters, "That's Zhang Binggui's son."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Binggui, who died in 1987, was a national model worker
for almost three decades. He joined the store in 1955 at the age
of 36, and set an immediate example by his enthusiasm and
dedication to his new job. He invented such skills as "yibazhun",
meaning that when a customer wanted, say, 500 grams of a
particular candy, Zhang would scoop up the precise amount at first
try. After his death, the government erected a statue to him in
front of the store.
</P>
<P>
Last August, the store re-opened after lengthy redecoration. It
also wanted new attractions for the customers, so Zhang Chaohe was
transferred from the toy counter to step into his father's shoes
and follow in his tradition.
</P>
<P>
Zhang the younger, 40, knows that he has an illustrious
tradition to uphold. Reminding him of his inheritance is a huge
grainy black and white photo of his father hanging behind the
circular sweet counter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
