<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Pursues FTAs With Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Singapore is pursuing free trade
agreements (FTAs) with several potential partners as a precaution
against possible trouble in the World Trade Organization (WTO),
Singapore Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong indicated at a
seminar Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Work Plan Seminar of the Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS), Lee, who is also MAS chairman, said, "We are
pursuing free trade agreements with several potential partners"
because "we need a fall-back position in case WTO runs into
trouble."
</P>
<P>
"After the fiasco of the Seattle ministerial meeting, such a
scenario has become less unlikely," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that Singapore has benefited from trade
liberalization at the WTO, Lee said FTAs will lead to further
opening up of the financial sector and other countries are doing
the same, citing the market enlargement of the European Union, the
expected establishment of a Free Trade Area of the Americas and
the idea of a North Asia free trade area.
</P>
<P>
The EU is enlarging its markets through FTAs with East European,
African and Latin American economies. North and South Americas,
including the United States, aim to conclude a Free Trade Area of
the Americas by 2005. Japan and South Korea have mooted the idea
of a Northeast Asia FTA.
</P>
<P>
"But otherwise, amidst this flurry of activity, Asia has been
conspicuously quiet," the deputy prime minister underlined.
</P>
<P>
Lee emphasized that the FTA strategy is an insurance policy for
his country, saying FTAs will keep Singapore away from being "left
out in the cold, should a weakened WTO fail to protect our
interests."
</P>
<P>
Singapore has embarked on FTA negotiations with New Zealand,
Japan and some South American countries in addition to its
involvement in the FTA plan of the ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Lee said every partner in negotiations with Singapore will ask
for bilateral trade concessions beyond what his country has
committed in WTO and many of them want preferential market access
in services, particularly in financial service.
</P>
<P>
"For the U.S., this would be a major motivation for their
considering an FTA with Singapore," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Singapore financial institutions must clearly brace themselves
for the greater competition this development would bring," the
deputy prime minister stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Exports Grow in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine exports grew by 13
percent to 2.9 billion U.S. dollars in February 2000 from 2.57
billion dollars a year earlier, the National Statistics Office
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Merchandise exports for the first two months of this year
increased by 9.1 percent to 5.62 billion dollars from 5.15 billion
dollars in 1999, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Exports of electronics and components, which accounted for 51
percent of total shipments, rose 8 percent to 1.48 billion dollars
in February from 1.37 billion dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Accounting for 89 percent of the total exports, manufactured
goods posted a 15.2-percent increase as sales reached 2.58 billion
dollars in February, up from 2.24 billion dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, incomes from agro-based products reached 141
million dollars in February, or 4.9 percent of the total. Compared
with last year, aggregate revenue for these products grew by 54
percent.
</P>
<P>
The United States remained the top market for Philippine goods
in February, taking up 30.3 percent or 878.21 million dollars of
all exports.
</P>
<P>
Japan was second with a 15.3-percent share or 444.94 million
dollars, 28 percent higher than that of February 1999.
</P>
<P>
Other major markets for Philippine goods were the Netherlands,
Singapore, Taiwan, Britain, Hong Kong, Germany, South Korea and
Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
