<HEADLINE> COMESA to Set Up Two Engineering Firms in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) is working on an engineering project with
two giant steel manufacturers in the sub-region to open two steel
and engineering works companies in Zambia, a senior official has
said.
</P>
<P>
Sindiso Ngwenya, COMESA assistant secretary-general, was quoted
by Monday's Zambia Daily Mail newspaper as saying that the opening
of these companies comes after the successful implementation of a
steel works program between Zimbabwe's Zisco Steel Makers which
has been running for the past three years.
</P>
<P>
The development of steel works in the regional grouping's
member states is one of the many projects which the COMESA embarks
on to make the area a successful trading place and economic
center, he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the expanding steel works between Kenya and
Zimbabwe as testimony of the authority's determination to ensure
that development takes root in the region and spreads to all other
member countries.
</P>
<P>
"In Zimbabwe, we have the largest steel works manufacturing
plant. The plant has been at the center of activities in the last
three years that cooperation was enhanced between the two
countries and as COMESA, we're happy that integration is not only
in the area of zero-rating on tariffs but in company expansions as
well," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Ngwenya, COMESA has trained 500 maintenance
engineers in the region to enhance the steel works operations and
engineering in the sub- region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
