<HEADLINE> Zambia Issues 125 Mining Exploration Licences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has over the
past year issued 125 mining exploration licences, some of which
are expected to result in development of new mines, the Times of
Zambia newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Mines Minister Syamukayumbu Syamujaye as
saying that these licences were issued to both local and foreign
investors as it is the only way the mining industry could develop
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Among the companies issued with exploration licences is
Caledonia, a British company engaged in exploration work on a
diamond mine in the Western Province of Zambia, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said Caledonia has finished exploring the prospective
diamond mine and has taken the mineral deposit samples for
laboratory testing.
</P>
<P>
According to Syamujaye, mining is a major foreign exchange
earner for Zambia which needs to be fully developed.
</P>
<P>
The mines, once established, would help boost direct capital
inflows into the mining sector and reshape the economy. 
</P>
