<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Burundian Rebel Members Held at Dar Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Three members of a Burundian
armed rebel group are being held at the Dar es Salaam
International Airport (DIA) for entering Tanzania without valid
travel documents, the Guardian newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The trio of the rebel group PALIPEHUTU-FLN (the Hutu People's
Liberation Party-the National Liberation Force), including the
leader Kabura Korsan, were arrested last Wednesday on arrival at
the DIA from South Africa where they had gone for consultations
with international mediator in the Burundi conflict, Nelson
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mark Bomani, head of the Burundi facilitation team, confirmed
that the FLN delegates, whose names could not be obtained, were
until the end of the week in the hands of the Tanzanian
immigration authorities.
</P>
<P>
The long-running peace talks between the Burundian government
and opposition groups have been handicapped by the absence of two
main armed Hutu rebel groups, FNL and CNDD-FDD (the National
Defense Council of Democracy-the Defense Force of Democracy).
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, the two main groups made a conditional promise
to Mandela to join the next round of talks scheduled for 25 April,
this year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, fighting between Hutu rebels and the
Tutsi-dominated army in the tiny central African country has
killed more than 200,000 Burundians and uprooted more than 1.2
million others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
