<HEADLINE> Zambian Striking Doctors Agree to Resume Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's resident doctors who
withdrew their labor last December have agreed to resume work
after their proposals are ratified, the Times of Zambia newspaper
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Resident Doctors Association of Zambia (RDA) general secretary
Canisius Banda disclosed on Sunday that his executive had a very
fruitful meeting with Health Minister David Mpamba.
</P>
<P>
After a number of consultations, the doctors met Mpamba for the
crucial meeting at which they integrated their proposals and
prepared a document for ratification, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have made a number of proposals and we will resume work
immediately after they are ratified," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the proposals included improved conditions of service
and an inducement allowance for doctors working in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
RDA had recommended that doctors working in rural areas should
be getting about 30-40 percent of their basic salaries as an
allowance to motivate them because of the hardships they go
through.
</P>
<P>
It also demanded that the recently bought drugs which were
locked up at the government's stores should be distributed in the
government's hospitals. 
</P>
