<HEADLINE> Pacific Plate Moving Causes New Zealand's Earthquakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The Pacific plate moving under
the Australasian plate, which New Zealand is on, caused the
earthquakes in New Zealand last week, The Dominion reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Wellington was rocked twice in a week. On Saturday morning it
was jolted by an earthquake measuring 5.3 on the Richter scale,
centered about 20 kilometers from Picton, a town on South Island,
at a depth of 50 kilometers. It followed a similar one on Thursday
morning measuring 5.7, centered 10 kilometers northwest of
Greytown, a town on North Island.
</P>
<P>
Several aftershocks were felt, including one measuring 4.4 and
another measuring 4. Both stemmed from the Picton quake.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted Ken Gledhill, a
seismologist at the Institute of Geological and Nuclear Sciences
of New Zealand, as saying that both the Greytown quake and Picton
quake were caused by the Pacific plate moving.
</P>
<P>
"In both places there'll be aftershocks for the next couple of
weeks. It is possible that either of these earthquakes will lead
on to something bigger but it's unlikely," Gledhill said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
