<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Trade Surplus Narrows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's trade balance was
in surplus in February 2000 for the 28th consecutive month, but
the amount has narrowed against that in the same month a year.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released here Monday by the Statistics
Department, the trade surplus recorded in February this year stood
at 4.7 billion ringgit (1.236 billion U.S. dollars) against a
surplus of 4.9 billion ringgit (1.289 billion U.S. dollars)
recorded in the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
This was due to a higher import growth of 32.6 percent vis-a-
vis that of exports which rose by 24.4 percent, the department
said.
</P>
<P>
Total exports and imports in the review month amounted to 27.2
billion ringgit (7.157 billion U.S. dollars) and 22.5 billion
ringgit (5.921 billion U.S. dollars) respectively as against
exports of 21.8 billion ringgit (5.736 billion U.S. dollars) and
imports of 17 billion ringgit (4.473 billion U.S. dollars) a year
earlier, the statistics show.
</P>
<P>
For the first two months of the year 2000, Malaysia registered
a trade surplus of 9.1 billion ringgit (2.394 billion U.S. dollars)
against a surplus of 9.2 billion ringgit (2.421 billion U.S.
dollars) in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
