<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Aboriginal Activist Attacks Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Aboriginal activist Charles
Perkins Accused Monday the Australian Federal government of being
racist.
</P>
<P>
Perkins was quoted by AAP as saying that drawing a parallel
between the stolen generation and the Jewish Holocaust was
legitimate because the principle was the same, whatever the
difference in the number of people killed.
</P>
<P>
Aboriginal children had been took away from their parents to
governmental organizations and white men's home under a policy of
national assimilation, whom people call "the stolen generation".
</P>
<P>
Aboriginal Affairs Minister John Herron denied Sunday there had
been ever "the stolen generation" saying that the term was a
misnomer.
</P>
<P>
Perkins warned against a demonstration during the Sydney
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
"It's burn, baby, burn from now on. Anything can happen."
</P>
<P>
When asked what he meant, Perkins said: "I'm talking about
demonstrations."
</P>
<P>
"This country is a racist country and it will pay in the
oncoming generations for what they are doing at the present time,"
he said adding that "This man here (Aboriginal Affairs Minister
John Herron), and this prime minister, are the worst we've ever
had. Not so much Herron, he's just a messenger boy for Howard."
</P>
<P>
National relations between the Australian government and
Aboriginals have been intense since a 15-years-old Aboriginal boy
suicided in custody in the Northern Territory on 10 February. He
was sentenced by the "Mandatory Sentencing Law" to 28 days of
detention for stealing stationery valued about 30 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
There are Mandatory Sentencing laws only in the Northern
Territory and the Western Australian state where most Aboriginals
of the country are living.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard refused to interfere in the local
judicature though believed himself the law was not good. His
attitude caused criticism not only from Aboriginals but also from
the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
