<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Suffers Stroke, Aoki Named Acting Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
has suffered a stroke and is in intensive care in a Tokyo hospital,
said Chief Cabinet Secretary Mikio Aoki on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Aoki has been appointed acting prime minister by Obuchi when
he visited the prime minister in hospital on Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
"Obuchi said we could not have any delay in our measures to
cope with the volcanic eruption so he appointed me as acting prime
minister," Aoki told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi won't be able to return to his duties for two or three
days, Aoki said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, 62, was hospitalized at Tokyo's Juntendo University
Hospital early Sunday for exhaustion and transferred to the
intensive care unit at about 8 p.m. Sunday (1100 GMT). His
condition was kept secret for 22 hours.
</P>
<P>
At Monday's news conference, Aoki refused to specify on
Obuchi's condition. Asked by journalists if Obuchi's illness was
life-threatening, Aoki said, "I don't know." He also refused to
comment on whether the prime minister was operated on.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi's illness is expected to have little immediate impact
on the government's day-to-day operations. However, his
hospitalization, if prolonged, may affect the summit of the Group
of Eight most industrialized nations scheduled for July in Okinawa,
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Aoki said he would call an emergency meeting of the cabinet at
about noon Monday to discuss the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi has had a heavy schedule over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The Mount Usu volcano in the northern island of Hokkaido
erupted on Friday after dormant for more than 20 years, forcing
tens of thousands of residents to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi was also in talks with the Liberal Party, a ruling
alliance of his Liberal Democratic Party. He failed to stop the
Liberal Party to quit the ruling coalition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
