<HEADLINE> Elian's Father Ready to Go to U.S. Alone, Castro Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is a change to an earlier proposal that a 30-member
delegation will accompany Juan Miquel Gonzalez to the United
States as there have been objections from the U.S. side, according
to Castro speaking on national television.
</P>
<P>
Elian, who is currently under the custody of his great uncle,
Lazaro Gonzalez, in Florida, was rescued on November 25 last year
from a shipwreck after his mother and 11 others died when the boat
capsized in the sea off Florida.
</P>
<P>
The president quoted Elian's father as saying that "If it's a
case of handing the boy over for his immediate return to Cuba, I
am ready to leave tomorrow, Monday, April 3, absolutely alone,"
adding it is up to Washington to decide.
</P>
<P>
However, Castro said, quoting Miquel Gonzalez, that if it takes
two months for a U.S. appeals court to rule on Elian's case, the
father and relatives still want an accompany by a delegation
during the trip to the United States. 
