<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Trade-Related News in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Groupama-Gan, France's second largest composite insurance
group, submitted an application for property and casualty
insurance license to the China Insurance Regulatory Commission (
CIRC).
</P>
<P>
-- Hutchison Port Holdings and Oracle Corporation announced
Monday the formation of the Global Transport eXchange (GTX), the
first worldwide on-line exchange for the transportation services
community.
</P>
<P>
-- BP Amoco and Petro China have reached an initial agreement
that the former will take 20 percent of the shares currently being
offered, up to a maximum of one billion US dollars, by Petro China
through its initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
-- Sina.com, one of China's most popular portal Internet sites,
announced Tuesday that it has filed a registration statement with
the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission in connection with its
initial public offering (IPO) of ordinary shares.
</P>
<P>
-- The China National Offshore Oil Corporation (CN00C) and
Burlington Resources China Ltd. of the United States Tuesday
signed a contract to explore a new block of oil resources in the
South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
-- The France-based IT company Alcatel is planning to sell one
million handsets of cellular phones in China this year, a senior
company official said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
-- Samsung, an electronic giant of the Republic of Korea (ROK)
is building the second production line of computer chips at its
joint venture in Suzhou city in east China's Jiangsu province.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S.-based Du Pont Company will continue to expand its
market share in China this year and build businesses in China into
its production base in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
-- Guangdong Province is willing to expand its areas of
cooperation with the Ericsson corporation in telecommunications in
the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
-- China's first European joint venture accounting firm
announced Tuesday it could give the CPA (certificate public
accountant) business a critical lift before China's entry into the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
