<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Trade-Related News in China (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- MOFTEC Minister Shi Guangsheng and Jim Sutton, minister for
trade negotiations of New Zealand, agreed Monday to further
develop and promote bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
-- China and New Zealand should make joint efforts to keep
bilateral trade growing and expand cooperation in agriculture,
forestry, and animal husbandry, a senior official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
State Councilor Wu Yi told Jim Sutton that business cooperation
opportunities between the two countries are huge as their
economies are complementary, especially when China is implementing
its strategy of developing its vast western region.
</P>
<P>
-- The good relations between the leaders of China and
Kazakhstan not only guarantee the development of bilateral trade,
but also inject new vitality into it, and sound bilateral
political ties have laid the foundation for the further
advancement of two-way trade, said Kuanysh Sultanov, the
Kazakhstan ambassador to China.
</P>
<P>
 Others
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin Friday told Frank Carlucci,
chairman of the Nortel Networks of Canada, that cooperation
between China and Canada should enjoy greater progress.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo met Thursday with Gary
Tooker, former chief executive officer (CEO) of the U.S.-based
Motorola Corporation.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo met Thursday with visiting
Yugoslav Minister of Telecommunications Ivan Markovic who is here
to sign a cooperation agreement with the Chinese side regarding
telecommunications construction.
</P>
<P>
-- In 20 years China will have the second-largest economy in
the world, with its economy shifting to a knowledge-based service
one, a senior World Bank official said.
</P>
<P>
"If you project current growth trends out 20 years you'll see
that China will no longer be the tenth largest trading partner in
the world but probably number two," the Hong Kong Standard Monday
cited Yukon Huang, the World Bank official in charge of the Bank's
operations in China, as saying.
</P>
<P>
-- Thirty-six companies nationwide authorized to carry out
international tendering business in China received certificates of
qualifications Thursday.
</P>
<P>
-- Latest statistics show that the total foreign investment in
Beijing increased by 1.6 percent on a year-on-year basis in the
first two months of this year to hit 295 million US dollars in
contractual value.  
</P>
</TEXT>
