<HEADLINE> Former Croatian Foreign Minister Founds New Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A new political party called the
Croatian Democratic Center was founded on Sunday with former
deputy prime minister and foreign minister Mate Granic as its head.
</P>
<P>
In a speech after his election, Granic announced that bringing
Croatia into the European Union and the North Atlantic Treaty
Orgainzation was his party's diplomatic priority, Croatian Radio
and Television reported.
</P>
<P>
The party's domestic policy would be focused on the uplifting
of the lives of the low-income population.
</P>
<P>
Granic decided in March to quit the former ruling Croatian
Democratic Union (HDZ) to form a new party after he was defeated
as HDZ's presidential candidate by Stipe Mesic, a People's Party
figure.
</P>
<P>
The formation of the new party symbolizes the open split of the
HDZ once controlled by late president Franjo Tudjman, who died on
December 10, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Granic, a moderate member of the HDZ, left the party among
disputes with hard-liners. Granic blamed the HDZ's internal
bickering for his defeat in the presidential race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
