<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Tory Leader to Fight On for Party Label </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Tory leader Joe Clark
Sunday vowed to fight on for the exclusive use of the party label
"Conservative."
</P>
<P>
Clark told reporters in Victoria, British Columbia, that he
would bring to the Federal Court of Canada later this month a
ruling by Elections Canada that the new party of the Canadian
Reform Conservative Alliance can keep the sensitive word "
Conservative."
</P>
<P>
Chief Electoral Officer Jean-Pierre Kingsley ruled early in the
day that "the proposed name Canadian Reform Conservative Alliance
does not so nearly resemble the name of any of the parties in our
registry so as to likely be confused with any of those parties."
</P>
<P>
In an immediate counter-argument, Clark stated "that name --
Conservative -- has been our name historically. It's our name."
</P>
<P>
"It is the name by which we have been known for more than a
century, the name under which Macdonald formed the country and
formed the party," said the Tory leader.
</P>
<P>
"We have fought and won elections across the country under that
name for all of that time," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Led by the country's official opposition leader Preston Manning,
the Reform Party voted last weekend to take the new name of the
Canadian Reform Conservative Alliance to represent a broader-based
party of both Reformers and provincial Conservatives, mainly from
Alberta and Ontario.
</P>
<P>
Manning urged Reformers to "think big" in favor of a more
powerful conservative political movement so as to prevent the
Liberals from a third successive win in the next federal elections.
</P>
<P>
The Reform party, which has its roots in western Canada and
enjoys 60 seats in the House of Commons, is looking forward to
having support of the ruling Conservatives in Ontario, which
accounts for no less than 103 of the 301 Parliament seats.
</P>
<P>
Unlike provincial Conservatives, or the so-called "small-c
conservative movement," the federal Progressive Conservatives
prefer to remain an independent opposition party in Parliament
with 20 seats.
</P>
<P>
Clark has repeatedly argued against the use of "Conservative"
by the Canadian Alliance and has asked Elections Canada to block
the attempts by the new party to pass itself off to voters as a
union between Reformers and Conservatives as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
