<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Market in Scenic City to be Restored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The government of south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region will allocate 11 million yuan (
about 1.3 million U.S.dollars) for restoring a 2,200-year-old
trading market in its famous scenic city of Guilin.
</P>
<P>
Known as Daxu Town, the market first appeared in 200 B.C. and
grew into a brisk trading center and became most famous by Ming
Dynasty (1368-1644) when businessmen from across the country came
to make fortune there.
</P>
<P>
The investment will be used to construct gate towers, ancient-
style residential houses and shops, said local sources.
</P>
<P>
The entire reconstruction project will be finished later this
year.
</P>
<P>
The move is considered as a way to attract more tourists to
Guilin, also an old city with a history of more than 2,000 years
and renowned for its green mountains, clear water and strangely-
shaped stone formations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Green Lottery" Proposed For Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, April 3 (Xinhua) -- A government advisor in east
China's Zhejiang Province has proposed that China run a "green
lottery" to support the national afforestation campaign.
</P>
<P>
Shao Shusheng, a member of the Jiande Municipal Committee of
Zhejiang Province of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), said the task of preventing soil erosion and
desertification is formidable, and it is very difficult for the
government to allocate sufficient funds for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
So a "green lottery" might help solve the problem, he said." I
believe many people will buy lottery tickets because people
nowadays are more conscious of environmental protection," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested the lottery should strongly emphasize the
theme of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
China's vegetation and afforestation coverage is only 13
percent and the per capital coverage is only 11.3 percent of the
world average. The country's desertification is so serious that it
has hindered the development of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Realizing the seriousness of the problem, China's State Council
last year called on all localities to reclaim barren hills, plant
trees, and create green belts in coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
China began issuing lotteries in 1987 and has sold some 35
billion yuan (4.2 billion U.S. dollars) worth of tickets in the
past 12 years.
</P>
<P>
China now has sports, welfare, education, and computer
lotteries, all very popular among Chinese citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
