<HEADLINE> On-line College Attracts Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 3 (Xinhua) -- China's first Internet-based
university opened to the public over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
This Web College, sponsored by the Continuous Education
Institute of Qinghua University and the Information Center of
Beijing Science and Technology Committee, is designed to "train
professionals in specialized skills".
</P>
<P>
Offering courses on computer science and product quality
appraisals, the web college will mainly recruit students in
Beijing, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Sun Xuewei, the institute's representative, said students are
able to choose their own courses and get credit for them.
</P>
<P>
Students' questions will be answered by on-line forums and
discussions, and examinations will be held annually at Qinghua
University.
</P>
<P>
By applying at the Information Center of Beijing Science and
Technology Committee, students are required to pay 15 yuan (1.8 U.
S. dollars) for every 50 minutes of time logged on to the course
websites.
</P>
<P>
However, the web college only offers courses on specialized
skills and does not issue academic degrees, Sun said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the information center indicate that about 500
people have so far expressed interest in taking courses at the web
college. 
</P>
</TEXT>
