<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, April 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- An attack on two men has increased fears in Northern
Ireland's Chinese community, the Chinese Welfare Association said
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The police said the attack on two Chinese men in south Belfast
on Sunday morning was racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
Both men were chased and beaten by a gang near Delhi Street, in
the Ormeau Road area of the city. One of the men was taken to
hospital with a broken finger and a head wound. (N.Ireland-Racist
Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- Thousands of Ugandans gathered in Kanungu in
southwestern part of the country Sunday afternoon to mourn the
over 920 victims of the cult Movement for the Restoration of Ten
Commandments of God.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony, presided over by Vice President Specioza Kazibwe,
was also attended by diplomats and ordinary foreigners.
</P>
<P>
In a key-note speech, Kazibwe urged religious leaders to offer
proper guidance to their followers. She described the Kanungu
incident, in which over 530 people were burnt to death in a church
fire on March 17, as a mass murder and the cult leaders as "
ruthless religious maniacs." (Uganda-Murder-Mourning)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President-elect Vladimir Putin will be sworn
in on May 7, Russia's Central Election Commission (CEC) chairman,
Alexander Veshnyakov, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We have scheduled a sitting of the Central Election Commission
for April 5 to sum up official results of the March 26 Russian
presidential election. The commission will officially publish its
resolution through the press on April 7. Under the law, the
inauguration of the president should take place 30 days after the
official publishing of the election results, that is on May 7,
2000," Veshnyakov told the Russian RTR television. (Russia-Putin-
Inauguration)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The foreign ministers of African and the European
Union (EU) states Sunday ended a one-day meeting in Cairo aimed at
making final preparations for the first, two-day Africa-Europe
summit due on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers reached agreement on the summit agenda
involving economic, political and social issues in Africa and ways
of enhancing cooperation over these issues between Africa and the
EU, Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama told reporters after
the meeting. (Africa-EU-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The loss of the Russia's special police commando
ambushed by rebels last Wednesday near the village of Dzhanoi-
Vedeno, south of the Chechen capital of Grozny, has added up to 43,
the Interfax news agency said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Chechen rebels' ambush on a Russian OMON police convoy, and
their subsequent surprise attack against a second, federal relief
convoy, cost the federal units 43 men killed in all, said Russia's
deputy commandant of Vedeno district Colonel Ilya Lukin. (Russia-
Chechnya-Toll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi was taken to a
Tokyo hospital Sunday morning for "over-exhaustion", Chief Cabinet
Secretary Mikio Aoki said Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the premier's condition was unknown, Aoki said,
adding that it will be disclosed as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Aoki would be named acting prime minister, if necessary. That
had not been done as of late Sunday, Aoki said, but the
possibility was under consideration. (Japan-PM-Sickness) 
</P>
</TEXT>
