<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgian Wins Home Leg of World Cup Cycling Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian-born Belgian Andrei
Tchmil on Sunday won the second leg of this year's 10-race World
Cup cycling tour by taking the Tour des Flandres.
</P>
<P>
The 37-year-old reigning World Cup titlist proved his flare and
form by pedalling away from the main pack some 11 kilometers from
finish after the gruelling climb out of a 269-kilometer race from
Bruges to Meerbeke just outside Brussels.
</P>
<P>
His winning time was six hours 57 minutes 3 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Dario Pieri finished four seconds behind as runner-up,
followed by Latvia's Romans Vainsteins.
</P>
<P>
Erik Zabel of Germany, winner of the opening leg of the World
Cup tour in Italy, finished fourth, but still kept his overall
leadership on the classification roster with 140 points. Second
now is Tchmil with 108 points.
</P>
<P>
"It's one of the best days in my life," said the winner. "I
gave it all I had and it was fantastic."
</P>
<P>
Peter van Petegem also of Belgium finished eighth, also four
seconds adrift the winner.
</P>
<P>
The Bruges-Meerbeke race consisted of asphalt and cobblestone
roads and several climbs in northwest Belgium. Tchmil described
Sunday's race course as "in my eyes the most beautiful course on
the World Cup circuit".
</P>
<P>
This year's World Cup tour ends in October with the Tour de
Lombardie. 
</P>
</TEXT>
