<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait Airways Corporation (KAC) announced on
Sunday that it will add one more flight to Beirut every week,
bringing to seven its weekly flights to the Lebanese capital.
</P>
<P>
The new flight will be operated every Monday, said Director of
Public Relations and Information in KAC, Adel Bourisli, in a press
statement.
</P>
<P>
Bourisli said the flight was added to meet the growing demand on
KAC's Kuwait-Beirut route.
</P>
<P>
KAC also raised its weekly flights to Jordan to four.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- A partnership agreement was signed here on Sunday
between Yemen's Ministry of Oil and Mineral Wealth, Saba National
Cooperation for Petroleum and Yemeni Cooperation for Oil
Investment, on one hand, and two U.S. firms, namely ADEAR and
Accidental, on the other.
</P>
<P>
The agreement covers an area of 2,049 square kilometers in
Sector No. 20, Shabwa Province, some 400 kilometers north Sanaay.
</P>
<P>
Yemen produces 400,000 barrels of oil a day. The proven oil
reserve amounts to six billion barrels and the gas reserve amounts
to 500 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Industries Minister Gholamreza Shafei on
Monday underlined expansion of the country's export, saying that
meeting domestic requirements and promoting exports are among the
priorities of the industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Saveh, the Central Province, Shafei said the country
needs to increase production in various industries and
industrialists should not neglect the potential for exports to
international markets.
</P>
<P>
"We have to gain a foothold in international markets by looking
to export," he said, adding that Iran can boost its exports in
various industrial sectors such as glassware and mines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
