<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Wishes Obushi Speedy Recovery from Stroke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Monday wished Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi of Japan a speedy
recovery from the effects of a stroke.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in San Hose, Calif., where he arrived for a speech,
Clinton said: "The thoughts and prayers of the American people are
with him, his family and the people of Japan. We hope for a speedy
recovery."
</P>
<P>
"It's a sad news for all of us here in America. But we're
pulling for his recovery, and we will keep our prayers there," he
added, adding that Obuchi has been "a good friend of me personally,
a god friend of the United States."
</P>
<P>
Clinton promised to work with acting Prime Minister Mikio Aoki
"to maintain the strong relationship we enjoy."
</P>
<P>
Obuchi suffered a stroke earlier on Monday and he is on life
support in Tokyo now.
</P>
<P>
The State Department said that Obuchi's illness will have no
affect on U.S. relations with Japan, including preparations for
the G-8 summit to be held in Okinawa this summer.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright "reiterated to acting Prime Minister Aoki and
Foreign Minister (Yohei) Kono American support for and confidence
in Japan's interim government and offers whatever help we can
during this difficult time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
