<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. High-Tech Industry, NAM Support PNTR for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Declaring the "PNTR is the single most important priority for
high-tech companies," the U.S. High-Tech Industry Coalition CEO
letter urges Congressional members to give their "strong support"
for extending PNTR status to China.
</P>
<P>
"We consider (the PNTR) vote the most critical vote you will
make in support of our high technology industries this year," said
the letter.
</P>
<P>
Citing China as a huge critical and fast growing market for
high-tech products and services, the letter said the fruits of
those many years of tough negotiating are at risk if Congress does
not establish PNTR with China.
</P>
<P>
Jim Whittaker of Hewlett-Packard Company, Chairman of the U.S.
High-Tech Industry Coalition on China, echoed the letter:"Now the
U.S. Congress needs to take its own step by making permanent the
same normal trade relations status that it has already been
approving annually for the past twenty years."
</P>
<P>
The coalition is made up of the leading technology associations
representing thousands of small to large technology companies from
around the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The Republican House leadership thanked the high-tech industry
CEOs for the letter's strong endorsement of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
"The overwhelming response from high-tech America, demonstrated
by this letter, underscores the importance of the China PNTR vote
this year. Opening markets around the world to American high-tech
products is crucial to keeping our economy vibrant and growing,"
said House majority Leader Dick Armey.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the National Association of Manufacturers (NAM)
Monday also called for PNTR with China at a news conference with
House Majority Leader Dick Armey.
</P>
<P>
"The facts are striking. Eighty-two percent of U.S. companies
that export to China are small and medium-sized firms and they all
want passage with PNTR with China," said NAM President Jerry
Jasinowski.
</P>
<P>
"They are not strangers to doing business overseas and are
committed to establishing PNTR with China because of the direct
connection to economic growth and jobs," he said. "The success of
our export strategy has always depended on a partnership between
smart manufacturers and results-oriented trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The NAM, the nation's largest and oldest multi-industry trade
association, represents 14,000 members (including 10,000 small and
mid-sized companies) and 350 member associations serving
manufacturers and employees in every industrial sector and all 50
states.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German CDU Chooses Polenz New General Secretary: Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Germany's troubled opposite
Christian Democrats (CDU) is due to pick Ruprecht Polenz as its
new general secretary to succeed Angela Merkel, the local media
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Polenz, the CDU legislator and deputy party leader in North
Rhine-Westphalia, is a lawyer in the city of Muenster in western
Germany.
</P>
<P>
He is set to be formally appointed at the party congress next
week, said the ZDF television and the Bild Zeitung daily.
</P>
<P>
Merkel, who is expected to be elected party leader at the same
congress, chose Polenz last weekend after two weeks of search,
said the Bild Zeitung. She also recommended Polenz into the CDU
presidium.
</P>
<P>
Merkel will inform a party executive session Tuesday her first
personnel appointment since she was tipped to lead the party last
month, reported the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Polenz himself did not comment on the reports, nor the CDU
spokesman gave any confirmation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guatemala to Look For Foreign Arbitration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The arbitration will strengthen Guatemala's position in the
dispute, said Villagran, member of Council of Belize, according to
reports reaching here from Guatemala's capital.
</P>
<P>
Sweden, Spain, Argentina and Venezuela are among nations to
which Cuatemala would request help, said the official whose
council directs his country's negotiating of this problem.
</P>
<P>
Guatemala is demanding Belize the return of 12,000 square
kilometers of land or that this dispute be submitted to
international arbitration which is being rejected by Belize's
government.
</P>
<P>
The land dispute between Guatemala and has its origin in a
border treaty signed in 1859 between Guatemala and Britain.
</P>
<P>
It would be convenient for Belize to look for the cooperation
of Canada or of certain African countries to solve this land
dispute, expressed the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
This controversy between Guatemala and Belize has engendered
several diplomatic, governmental and military brushings regarding
the border land between both nations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0354 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Museums to Cut Admission Cost Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Under plans to open up its cultural
heritage to a wider public, entry fees for many of England's
national museums could be cut to one pound (1.6 U.S. dollars) from
next year in a move which is likely to cost the government 7.1
million pounds.
</P>
<P>
The new charges, which fall short of the Labor government's
early aspirations to abolish entrance fees altogether, will take
effect from September 2001. People on welfare or with disabilities
will get in for free.
</P>
<P>
"I want to see the best of our culture and heritage made
available to the greatest possible number, regardless of their
income," Culture Secretary Chris Smith said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some leading national museums, including the British Museum
which attracts 5.5 million visitors a year, charge no entry fee.
</P>
<P>
Charges for others range from five pounds at the Victoria and
Albert Museum to 6.95 pounds at the Science Museum and 7.50 pounds
at the Natural History Museum.
</P>
<P>
Free admission at charging museums was introduced for children
last year and will be extended to the over-60s later this year.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time in 20 years, affordable access to the best
of our cultural heritage really will be available for the many,
not the few," Smith said.
</P>
<P>
But some museums -- like the Natural History Museum -- maintain
that they have been able to run successful and attractive museums
because of their charging policies.
</P>
<P>
There are also fears that if entrance is free, museums would
lose their status as businesses and would no longer be able to
reclaim VAT on building projects.
</P>
<P>
In February, a major funding boost for the new Tate Modern
Gallery drew accusations that the government would no longer be
able to afford to fund universal free access.
</P>
<P>
The art gallery on London's south bank is to receive an
injection of 5 million pounds in the coming financial year, with
year-on-year increases of 6 million pounds thereafter, to ensure
free admission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0355 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
