<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Pledges to Cancel Debts of Poorest Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 3 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
pledged on Monday that France will cancel debts of the poorest
countries within one or two years.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made the pledge while addressing the first Africa-Europe
summit opened here earlier in the day. But he neither gave the
figures of the debts that France will write off nor mentioned the
poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of some 67 African and European Union countries took
part in the summit to discuss economic, political and social issues
in African countries and African-EU cooperation in these fields.
</P>
<P>
Chirac called on the EU to provide substantial assistance to
African countries in view of its cooperation with them.
</P>
<P>
He urged African countries to carry on economic reforms in a bid
to address the challenges of globlization.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama told reporters
after the first session of the summit that Germany and Morocco will
also make contributions to the African debt relief.
</P>
<P>
Germany has promised to provide 700 million German marks (about
430 million U.S. dollars) for the relief effort, said Gama, whose
country is holding EU's rotating presidency for the first half of
2000. But Morocco did not announce the sum, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
