<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2100GMT, Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The United States will not send troops to fill the
vacuum areas in south Lebanon after Israel soldiers withdraw by
July, visiting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
Monday morning, Cohen also revealed that no final decisions had
made about the future of any international presence in the buffer
area.
</P>
<P>
Even if U.N. peacekeepers would be sent to ensure the quiet
along the border between Israel and Lebanon, Cohen suggested, U.S.
soldiers will not participate. (Israel-Lebanon-Withdrawal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar Zanganeh said here
on Monday that Iran seeks an oil output hike to preserve its share
in the world oil market but will not go for a production rise which
may ruin the market.
</P>
<P>
Iran is seeking a rise in oil production given the market
realities, Zanganeh stressed, adding its policy of not flooding the
market with additional oil does not mean that Iran will not
increase its production.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister did not disclose how many barrels Iran
would add to its current output of about 3.3 million barrels per
day, the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported. (Iran-
Oil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Africa-Europe Summit, the first and biggest
gathering between the two continents to forge a new and strategic
relationship, opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak inaugurated the summit at the
Cairo International Convention Center shortly after 3:00 p.m.
(1300GMT).
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the changes and achievements made in Africa and the
help given by Europe to the poor continent, Mubarak stressed in his
speech that Africa should integret itself in the economic
globalization and get along with the international changes.
</P>
<P>
"So the African leaders should take decisions for the
establishment of African federation programs and parliament," he
added. (Africa-Europe Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- An airplane carrying three persons from France and
Italy landed at the Al-Rashed military airport in Baghdad at 19:45
p.m. local time (1645 GMT), to protest the decade-long U.N. embargo
imposed on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
At the airport, Jean-Marie Benjamin, head of the delegation,
read a declaration to the local and foreign media who have been
waiting for more than seven hours.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration, Benjamin condemned the embargo and called
for an immediate lifting of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The three-member delegation got no prior permission from the U.
N., who imposed the devastating embargo on Iraq since its 1990
invasion of Kuwait. (Iraq-Europe-Plane)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Monday denied that
Israel offered a suggestion on the future Palestinian state during
the recent round of Washington talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat told reporters in the West Bank city of Bethlehem after
his meeting with European Union Commissioner of Foreign Affairs
Christopher Patin.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday Palestinian chief negotiator in the interim
talks with Israel Saeb Erekat ruled out the existence of Israeli
offer to establish a Palestinian state on 50 percent of the
occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator in the final status talks Yasser
Abed Rabbo was quoted on Sunday as saying that Israel suggested to
group all the Jewish settlement blocks in Israel. (Palestine-
Arafat-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- French President Jacques Chirac pledged on Monday that
France will cancel debts of the poorest countries within one or two
years.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made the pledge while addressing the first Africa-Europe
summit opened here earlier in the day. But he neither gave the
figures of the debts that France will write off nor mentioned the
