<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Index Suffers Worst Point Drop in History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 3 (Xinhua) -- The tech stocks fell sharply
Monday in advance of a judge's ruling in Microsoft's antitrust
case, dragging the technology heavy Nasdaq composite index down
about 350 points, the worst point drop in history.
</P>
<P>
At the close of session, the Nasdaq composite fell 349.15 at 4,
223.68, surpassing the plunge of 229.46 points on January 4.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 300.01 at 11,221.93 and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 7.39 at 1,505.97.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq index plunged before U.S. District judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson was expected to rule at 5 p.m. today on Microsoft
's guilt following a failure to reach an agreement on that case
between the software maker and the U.S. government Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft fell 16 1/4 to 90 U.S. dollars a share and brought
punishment to the Nasdaq index as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq has fallen 17 percent since the index set the record
closing high of 5,048.62 points March 10. A drop of 10 percent is
defined as a market correction.
</P>
<P>
While drawing money from tech stocks, investors made a shift to
blue chip shares, driving the Dow index higher.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 11.96 at 659.66. But the American Stock
Exchange index fell 27.03 at 978.00 and the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 23.03 at 516.04.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a slender margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,575 up, 1,517 down and 384
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 1.02 billion shares from 1.20 billion
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
