<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000403.0368 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Signs Convention to Prevent Terrorist Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia Monday signed the
Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism,
saying that "preventing terrorist financing is a crucial avenue in
the international cooperation to suppress the evil terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Sergey Lavrov, the Russian permanent representative to the
United Nations, entered his name on the Convention on behalf of
his government.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, the Russian Mission to the United
Nations said in a press release that "Russia views this instrument
as an important contribution to the strengthening of the
international legal regime for combating international terrorism."
</P>
<P>
"Preventing terrorist financing is a crucial avenue in the
international cooperation to suppress the evil terrorism," the
press release said. "The Chechen experience proves that."
</P>
<P>
"Russia reiterates its position to counter any acts of
terrorism, by whoever and wherever perpetrated, and irrespective
of the motivation involved, including by preventing and
suppressing in its territory the preparation and financing of
terrorism and denying terrorists safe havens," the press release
said.
</P>
<P>
"Russia has some specific concern about what has been provided
in Article 15 of the Convention, namely with respect to the
possibility of refusing in certain conditions the extradition and
legal assistance given with regard to crimes defined in this
Convention," the press release said.
</P>
<P>
"Upon signing, Russia has therefore made a declaration to the
effect that the position of the Russian Federation is that the
provision of Article 15 of the Convention should be implemented in
such a way as to ensure the inevitability of punishment for the
commission of offenses falling within the scope of the Convention,
without detriment to the effectiveness of international
cooperation related to extradition and legal assistance," it added.
</P>
<P>
The Convention was adopted on December 9, 2000 by the General
Assembly, and it was open for signature by all States at the U.N.
Headquarters in New York from January 10, 2000 to December 31,
2001.
</P>
<P>
So far, Russia is the 16th country to sign the Convention,
which shall enter into force on the 30th day following the date of
the deposit of the 22nd instrument of ratification, acceptance,
approval or accession with the Secretary-General of the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Convention demands signatories to adapt their domestic law
to make it a punishable crime the action to finance terrorism in
all forms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
